Mind Field : Season 1
description:
In Mind Field, host Michael Stevens brings his passion for science to his most ambitious subject yet: something we still know very little about, human behavior.
 
Using real subjects (including guest stars and Michael himself) Mind Field reveals some of the most mind-blowing, significant, and least-understood aspects of the human psyche.
 
Through expert interviews, rare footage from historical experiments, and brand-new, ground-breaking demonstrations of human nature at work, Mind Field explores the surprising things we know (and don‚Äôt know) about why people are the way they are.

title: Mind Field : Season 2
description: Creator/host Michael Stevens takes us on an even deeper dive into the mysterious depths of the human psyche.  Working with top Universities and cutting-edge Research Labs, Michael travels the world to explore the latest frontiers in psychology and neuroscience through groundbreaking demonstrations that test the powers and limits of the human mind.  From testing psychedelic drugs in the Amazon jungle to investigating how unsuspecting test subjects handle terrifying life-or-death decisions, each episode offers an unprecedented journey into the ever-shifting boundaries of the Mind Field.In the third season of Mind Field, creator/host Michael Stevens continues his never-ending quest to uncover the inner workings of the human mind. With unprecedented access to leading universities and researchers who are turning science fiction into science fact, Michael travels farther than he ever has before, designing demonstrations which put theories to the test in the real world.

title: Mind Field : Season 3
description: In the third season of Mind Field, creator/host Michael Stevens continues his never-ending quest to uncover the inner workings of the human mind. With unprecedented access to leading universities and researchers who are turning science fiction into science fact, Michael travels farther than he ever has before, designing demonstrations which put theories to the test in the real world.

title: Our Best Stuff
description: New here? Try these.

title: Black Holes
description: Black holes are the most mysterious and extreme objects in the universe‚Äîwhere physics itself breaks down. In this playlist, we explore the mind-bending science of black holes and the bizarre phenomena surrounding them. What happens if you fall into one? Is information truly lost forever, or does the paradox have an answer? Dive into strange ideas like black hole bombs, gravastars, and hypothetical black hole stars. We‚Äôll take you beyond the event horizon, into the realm of neutron stars and strange matter, where the rules of reality begin to blur. Discover the power of quasars‚Äîthe brightest beacons of the cosmos‚Äîand meet the largest black holes known, monsters millions of times the mass of our Sun. From the terrifying to the theoretical, this series is a journey to the edge of space, time, and understanding.

title: Climate Change
description: Climate change is the biggest challenge of our time‚Äîbut how did we get here? This playlist explores the roots of the crisis, tracing the historical, political, and economic forces that brought us to the brink. Who is truly responsible, and why is progress so difficult? We dive into the complex systems that make climate change so hard to beat and ask tough questions: Can individuals make a difference, or is it all about governments and corporations? What roles do fossil fuels, agriculture, and meat consumption play? And is nuclear power part of the solution‚Äîor a dangerous distraction? Through science-based storytelling and sharp visuals, we examine not just the problems, but also the potential paths forward. Whether you‚Äôre new to the topic or looking to deepen your understanding, this series is your guide to the messy truth about climate change‚Äîand what we can do about it.

title: Immune System
description: The immune system is one of the most complex and fascinating systems in the human body‚Äîa biological defense network shaped by millions of years of evolution. This playlist unpacks how it works, from the first line of defense to its most specialized soldiers, revealing how it protects us from threats like rabies, tuberculosis, and smallpox. But not all battles are won. We explore how the immune system struggles against cunning enemies like cancer, and how scientists are helping it fight back. What happens when viruses are genetically engineered‚Äîor when they evolve faster than we can respond? And what role do vaccines play in training our immune system and stopping pandemics before they start? From ancient plagues to cutting-edge biotechnology, this series dives deep into the inner workings of our most vital protector‚Äîand the invisible wars happening inside us every day.

title: Nuclear
description: Nuclear power is one of the most powerful‚Äîand controversial‚Äîforces humanity has ever harnessed. This playlist explores how nuclear energy works, its potential to help us fight climate change, and the risks that come with it. Are the benefits worth the danger? We break down the pros and cons, from clean electricity to radioactive waste. Speaking of waste‚Äîcould we just launch it into space? And how dangerous is nuclear energy, really? We look at the human cost of past nuclear accidents and the lessons they‚Äôve taught us. But the atom‚Äôs destructive side looms large: the threat of nuclear war still hangs over the world. What would happen if the worst came to pass? We dive into the terrifying concept of nuclear winter and what it means for life on Earth. Whether it‚Äôs energy or annihilation, this series unpacks the science and consequences of going nuclear‚Äîin all its forms.

title: Diseases
description: Diseases are nature‚Äôs oldest killers‚Äîand some of the most fascinating. This playlist takes you deep into the world of infectious threats and how our bodies respond. From the familiar misery of the common cold to the terrifying horror of rabies and brain-eating amoebas, we uncover what happens when tiny invaders hijack our biology. Explore the long history of tuberculosis and smallpox, the rise of giant viruses, and the unique ways they challenge our immune system. We also dive into cancer‚Äîa disease from within‚Äîand how it turns our own cells against us. Along the way, learn why fever can be both a symptom and a weapon, and how evolution, medicine, and chance all play a role in who gets sick and who survives. These are the invisible battles happening every day inside billions of bodies‚Äîincluding yours.

title: Drugs
description: Drugs shape our bodies, brains, and societies‚Äîoften in surprising ways. This playlist explores the science behind some of the most widely used and controversial substances. What does new research say about weed? Why are smoking and vaping so addictive and appealing, especially to young people? And how did fentanyl spark a deadly epidemic in the U.S.? We unpack the biology, psychology, and social impact of drugs‚Äîand what makes them so hard to resist.

title: Ants
description: Ants are tiny, but their worlds are vast, complex, and brutal. This playlist dives into the incredible lives of ants‚Äîlike the weaver ant, which builds kingdoms from leaves with silk and teamwork. Discover epic wars between ant species, where colonies rise and fall, and uncover the dark side of ant society: slavery, where some ants capture and exploit others. From strategy to survival, these stories reveal the alien intelligence and ruthless efficiency of the insect world.

title: Space Exploration
description: Space is vast, beautiful‚Äîand full of questions we‚Äôre only beginning to answer. This playlist explores humanity‚Äôs future among the stars: from building the first bases on the Moon and Mars to the dream of colonizing the entire solar system. But space isn‚Äôt empty. We examine the growing threat of space junk and how it could trigger a devastating chain reaction. What technologies could help us thrive beyond Earth? Enter the world of Dyson spheres, Caplan thrusters, and megastructures that could reshape our cosmic destiny. Along the way, we ask one of the biggest questions of all: Are we alone? What might alien life look like‚Äîand why haven‚Äôt we found it yet? The Great Filter may hold the answer. From bold visions to existential mysteries, this series takes you on a journey through the possibilities‚Äîand perils‚Äîof our future in space.

title: Deliver Us The Moon - Let's Play
World History
description:
In 42 episodes, John Green will begin teaching you the history of the world! This course is based on the 2012 AP World History curriculum, from growing the first crops in the First Agricultural Revolution to global textile production in the 2010s. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

*Identify and explain historical developments and processes
*Analyze the context of historical events, developments, and processes and explain how they are situated within a broader historical context
*Explain the importance of point of view, historical situation, and audience of a source
*Analyze patterns and connections among historical developments and processes, both laterally and chronologically through history
*Be a more informed citizen of the world

title: Biology (2012)
description:
In 40 videos, Hank Green teaches you biology! This course is based on the AP Biology curriculum and also covers some introductory anatomy. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Recognize the chemicals, molecules, and structures that make up living things 
* Understand the processes that keep organisms alive and drive cellular reproduction
* Identify evidence of evolution and explain its role in speciation, development, and anatomy
* Describe the characteristics of the different kingdoms and some phyla that make up the taxonomy of living things
* Predict how the interactions between molecules, cells, organisms, and populations contribute to larger systems

title: Ecology
description:
In 12 episodes, Hank Green teaches you ecology! This course is based on a college level introductory curriculum with the 9th edition of Campbell Biology by Reece, et al. as its base text.
By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Define ecological terms like population, ecosystem, community, and ecological succession
* Understand how competition and environmental changes positively and negatively affect populations
* Explain cycles of chemical resources and how they relate to ecosystems
* Contextualize the effects of human behavior from an ecological standpoint

title: Literature 1
description:
In 8 episodes, John Green dives into literature! The analyses and books chosen in this course are based on introductory college-level curriculum and the AP Literature guidelines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Use characters and setting to explore a range of values, beliefs, assumptions, biases, and cultural norms
*Discuss the role of the narrator and how their perspective affects how readers experience and interpret a text
*Recognize comparisons, representations, and associations that invite readers to interpret a text
*Explain the function of significant events in a plot, as well as the contributions of structure, sequence, contrast, and conflict
*Employ different lenses and focal points to read a text multiple ways and recognize the glorious ambiguity of literature
*Discuss how different texts employ time as a theme

title: US History
description:
In 48 episodes, John Green will teach you the history of the United States of America! This course is based off of the 2013 AP US History curriculum. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

* Identify the context and causes of historical developments throughout recorded US history
* Explain the similarities and differences between historical developments
* Understand the complexity of the American and national identity and values
* Describe how social structures, politics, power, and culture influence each other and historical developments
* Contextualize and complicate the common narratives of US history that explain the present

title: Chemistry
description:
In 46 episodes, Hank Green will teach you chemistry! This course is mostly based on the 2012 AP Chemistry curriculum, but it also covers some introductory organic chemistry. By the end of the course, you will be able to: 

* Utilize the fundamental tools of chemistry, including the periodic table, nomenclature, and basic lab safety techniques
* Understand the structure of matter
* Predict and explain chemical reactions, and comprehend the many ways they affect our world
* Reason through problems involving kinetics, thermodynamics, and chemical equilibrium
* Recognize different organic chemicals and their uses

We also made flashcards to help you review the content in this course! Find them on the free Crash Course App available for Apple devices in the App Store and Android devices in the Google Play store.

title: Psychology
description:
In 40 episodes, Hank Green will teach you psychology! This course is based on the 2013 AP Psychology curriculum. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

* Understand the biological basis of human behavior and perception
* Explain standard models of thinking, learning, and emotions 
* Recognize rigorous psychological research methods, including ethical considerations
* Identify cases of abnormal psychology and associated treatments
* Apply psychological theories to social groups

title: World History 2
description:
In 30 episodes, John Green rethinks world history! In round two we take a different approach and try to think more thematically rather than chronologically. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

*Think about history thematically and in terms of systems, not just important events
*Analyze the context of historical events, developments, and processes and explain how they are situated within a broader historical context
*Explain the importance of point of view, historical situation, and audience of a source
*Question how what we think of as ‚Äúhistory,‚Äù how it is written, and what biases are at play in a work

title: Big History
description:
In 10 episodes John Green, Hank Green, and Emily Graslie teach you about, well, everything. It‚Äôs Big History! This course will take you on a whirlwind journey from the creation to the death of the universe and is based on the Big History Project (https://www.bighistoryproject.com/about) social studies curriculum. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Integrate physics, math, history, and more to tell a single story about people, civilizations, and how we are connected to everything around us
*Zoom out to pose and refine scientific and historical questions
*Contextualize the tremendous scale of existence
*Outline the most powerful and important breakthroughs
*Evaluate how we know what we know and why we‚Äôre sure we know it

title: Anatomy & Physiology
description:
In 47 episodes, Hank Green will teach you anatomy and physiology! This course is based on an introductory college level curriculum, with Human Anatomy and Physiology, 9th edition, by Marieb and Hoehn as its main reference text. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

* Understand the chemistry and cell biology of systems in the human body
* Recognize how tissue types define the function of each organ system
* Predict how the failure of an organ system might lead to disease
* Explain how energy is changed into different forms throughout the body
* Break down the names of anatomical systems using Greek and Latin root words

We also made flashcards to help you review the content in this course! Find them on the free Crash Course App available for Apple devices in the App Store and Android devices in the Google Play store.

title: Astronomy
description:
In 46 episodes, Phil Plait (aka The Bad Astronomer) teaches you astronomy! This course starts with the astronomical observations we can make with the naked eye and expands out to cover the solar system, stars, galaxies, and the universe itself. The content is loosely based on an introductory university-level curriculum. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Define the components of the universe, from the planets in the Solar System to dark energy and gamma rays
* Understand how astronomers collect and analyze data to study the past and current state of the universe 
* Explain the difference between asteroids, comets, and meteors
* Contextualize observed phenomena within scientific theories about the history and physics of space, such as the Big Bang theory

title: U.S. Government and Politics
description:
In 50 videos, Craig Benzine (aka WeezyWaiter) teaches you U.S. government and politics! The course is based on the 2014 AP U.S. Government and Politics curriculum. By the end of this learning playlist, you will be able to:

* Become a more engaged and active citizen
* Understand how the US government works and how you can make it better for you and your community
* Explain the differences between the three branches of government
* Describe how political ideology, parties, and media influence elections and public policy
* Identify the limitations of democracy and the U.S. political system

title: Intellectual Property
description:
In 7 episodes, Stan Muller teaches you about Intellectual Property! This course introduces you to the concept and importance of intellectual property, and covers copyright, patents, international IP law and problems with intellectual property. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Define intellectual property, copyright, patents, and other relevant terms
* Complicate the idea of an intellectual property versus technology binary
* Understand the impact of intellectual property in your daily life and the wider community
* Describe the function of intellectual property from both a consumer and creator perspective

title: Economics
description:
In 35 episodes, Adriene Hill and Jacob Clifford teach you economics! This course is based on introductory college level curriculum and the 2015 AP Economics guidelines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Identify fundamental economic concepts, principles, or models and describe their similarities, differences, and limitations
*Apply economic analyses to everyday life and see economics in real world situations
*Discuss economic differences and similarities internationally and the roles played by various governments
*Determine the outcome of an economic situation using economic concepts, principles, or models and possible effects changes have on other economic markets

title: Philosophy
description:
In 46 episodes, Hank Green will teach you philosophy! This course is based on an introductory Western philosophy college level curriculum. By the end of the course, you will be able to: 

* Examine topics like the self, ethics, religion, language, art, death, politics, and knowledge through a philosophical perspective
* Craft arguments, apply deductive and inductive reasoning, and identify fallacies
* Understand the perspectives and major theories proposed by various philosophers throughout history
* Apply philosophical ideas to ethical questions in modern society
* Consider your personal values and approach to life

title: Physics
description:
In 46 episodes, Dr. Shini Somara will help you find your place in the world -- literally! -- with physics. This course is based on introductory college-level material and the 2016 AP Physics I and II curriculum. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Identify the fundamental forces describing the world and the core branches of physics
*Pose, refine, and evaluate scientific questions
*Connect phenomena and models across spatial and temporal scales
*Use representations and models to communicate scientific phenomena and solve scientific problems
*Apply mathematical equations that describe natural phenomena

title: Games
description:
In 29 episodes, Andre Meadows will teach you about games! This course was developed with The Art of Game Design: A Book of Lenses by Jesse Schell as a main reference text. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Comprehend, interpret, and analyze texts, games, animations, and imagery
* Discuss game-related problems and solutions in group settings
* Contextualize games according to historical period and psychological underpinnings 
* Understand how games are developed and how consoles and companies change over time
* Apply concepts to particular games and to examples from everyday life

title: Literature 3
description:
In 9 episodes, John Green reads even more literature! The analyses and books chosen in this course are based on introductory college-level curriculum and the AP Literature guidelines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Use characters and setting to explore a range of values, beliefs, assumptions, biases, and cultural norms
*Discuss the role of the narrator and how their perspective affects how readers experience and interpret a text
*Recognize comparisons, representations, and associations that invite readers to interpret a text
*Explain the function of significant events in a plot, as well as the contributions of structure, sequence, contrast, and conflict
*Employ different lenses and focal points to read a text multiple ways and recognize the glorious ambiguity of literature
*Discuss how different texts explore the theme of ‚Äúself‚Äù and how it is made

title: Computer Science
description:
In 40 episodes, Carrie Anne Philbin teaches you computer science! This course is based on introductory college-level material as well as the AP Computer Science Principles guidelines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Outline the history of computers and the design decisions that gave us modern computers
*Describe the basic elements of programming and software
*Identify the basic components of computer hardware and what they do
*Describe how computers are used and how that has evolved over time
*Appreciate how far computers have come and how far they might take us

title: World Mythology
description:
In 41 episodes, Mike Rugnetta will teach you world mythology! This course is based on introductory college-level curriculum spanning mythologies around the globe. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Define myth and decide what elements distinguish it from other narrative forms
*Connect myths around the world and identify how different cultures sought answers to similar big questions 
*Use myths to understand past civilizations, like by recognizing their core values
*Identify how the staying power of myths influence our beliefs and cultures today, like in our language

title: Crash Course Sociology
description:
In 44 videos, Nicole Sweeney will teach you sociology! This course is based on an introductory college level curriculum, with Sociology, 15th edition, by John J. Macionis as its reference text. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Understand what makes sociology a science and how sociological investigations occur
* Recognize the social institutions that operate within the United States and influence cultural norms
* Contextualize key sociological theories within history and the field of sociology
* Discuss the way social groupings, interactions, and stratifications are constructed within societies and construct our behavior
* Predict how social class, stratification, and institutions create or improve inequalities

title: Film History
description:
In 16 episodes, Craig Benzine will teach you about film history! This course is based on an introductory college level curriculum, with A History of Narrative Film by David A. Cook as its reference text. By the end of the course, you will be able to: 

* Understand that cinema is an illusion and how our brains make meaning out of still images placed side-by-side in rapid succession
* Discuss the birth of the moving picture and the innovations that made sound and color possible
* Explain how the studio system rose to power and then collapsed
* Contextualize the many uses of film around the globe, including as propaganda

title: Study Skills
description:
In 10 episodes, Thomas Frank teaches you study skills! Based on introductory college-level material and scientific studies, this course takes you through the tools and skills you need to get better at studying and finishing assignments in school and beyond. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Understand the advantages and disadvantages of different note-taking methods
* Recognize factors that inhibit productivity and solutions to get past them
* Feel better prepared to study for and take your next exam or finish your next assignment
* Analyze the connections between studying and memory, exercise, and studying

title: Statistics
description:
In 44 episodes, Adriene Hill teaches you Statistics! This course is based on the 2018 AP Statistics curriculum and introduces everything from basic descriptive statistics to data collection to hot topics in data analysis like Big Data and neural networks. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

*Identify questions that can be answered using statistics
*Describe patterns, trends, associations, and relationships in data both numerically and graphically
*Justify a conclusion using evidence from data, definitions, or statistical inference
*Apply statistical models to make inferences and predictions from data sets
*Understand how statistics are used broadly in the world and interpret their meaning, like in newspapers or scientific studies

title: Crash Course Theater and Drama
description:
In 50 videos, Mike Rugnetta teaches you theater and drama! This course is based on an introductory college level course in Theater and explores the history, theory, and technology that contributes to the art form most like life. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Describe the leading theories of the origins of theater
* Understand how theater was produced and what it meant to audiences around the world
* Analyze the historical and cultural contexts that lead to the creation of different movements in theater history
* Argue for the importance of producing and understanding theater

title: Media Literacy
description:
In 12 episodes, Jay Smooth teaches you Media Literacy! Based on an introductory college level curriculum, this series takes you through the history and psychology of media and gives you the skills to become more media savvy. By the end of this course, you‚Äôll be able to:
* Describe media literacy as a skill and its development over time
* Understand the positive and negative effects of media on audiences
* Explain how media regulations and policies affect media producers
* Create many forms of media in an informed way

title: History of Science
description:
In 46 episodes, Hank Green teaches you the history of science! This course is based on the 2nd and 3rd edition of Science & Technology in World History by McClellan & Dorn. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Thoughtfully consider the questions, ‚ÄúWhat is stuff?‚Äù and ‚ÄúWhere are we?‚Äù
* Understand science as a social and historical concept that varies between cultures
* Describe the development of the process and products of scientific inquiry over time 
* Explain how scientists influence society and society influences scientists
* Contextualize the limitations of scientific inquiry, from what we still don‚Äôt know to who has been excluded

title: Engineering
description:
In 46 episodes, Dr. Shini Somara will teach you how we built much of our world with engineering! This course is based on introductory college-level material across many different engineering disciplines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Consider the impact of engineering solutions in global, economic, environmental, and societal contexts
*Recognize ethical and professional responsibilities in engineering situations and make informed judgements
*Apply principles of engineering, science, and mathematics to identify and solve technical problems
*Discuss grand challenges and questions in engineering and progress on solutions

title: Navigating Digital Information
description:
In 10 episodes, John Green will teach you how to navigate the internet! We‚Äôve partnered with MediaWise, The Poynter Institute, and The Stanford History Education Group to develop this curriculum of hands-on skills to help you evaluate the information you read online. By the end of this course, you will be able to: 

* Examine information using the same skills and questions as fact-checkers
* Read laterally to learn more about the authority and perspective of sources
* Evaluate different types of evidence, from videos to infographics
* Understand how search engines and social media feeds work
* Break bad internet habits like impatience and passivity, and build better ones

title: Film Production with Lily Gladstone
description:
In 15 episodes, Lily Gladstone will teach you about film production! This course is based on an introductory college level curriculum and introduces practical skills you might learn in film school. By the end of the course, you will be able to: 

* Describe the production process of a film, from writing a screenplay to marketing the final product
* Recognize different departments and jobs on a film set and how they work together
* Notice camera and lighting techniques while watching films and understand what took place behind-the-scenes
* Name specific equipment and understand its purpose on a film set

title: Film Criticism
description:
In 15 episodes, Michael Aranda will teach you about film criticism! This course is based on an introductory college level curriculum and will teach by analyzing 15 films from different genres, directors, years, and countries. By the end of the course, you will be able to: 

* Acknowledge both the subjective and objective reasons that make a film "great" or "not great"
* Apply different critical lenses to any film that you watch
* Understand how filmmakers make choices that enhance the stories they're trying to tell
* Analyze films and their messages within the context of society, history, psychology, and the landscape of cinema

title: Business Soft Skills
description:
In 17 episodes, Evelyn From The Internets will teach you soft skills for business and everyday life! This course is based on a college-level curriculum, with a variety of management and organizational psychology reference texts. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

* Hone communication skills you already have to stand out in the workplace
* Tackle the job search and negotiate a job offer with organization and confidence
* Use time management strategies and set achievable personal and professional goals
* Navigate complex situations involving difficult conversations, fairness, power, and trust 
* Work with a team effectively, from understanding others‚Äô motivations to running a meeting

title: European History
description:
In 50 episodes, John Green will teach you about European History to give you an overview of Europe‚Äôs history and connection with the world from 1450 to the present. This course is based on the AP European History Course Description and college-level Introduction to Western Civilization curriculum. By the end of the course, you will be able to:
 
*Examine European events from 1450 to the present from multiple perspectives
*Explain the relative historical significance of specific historical developments in relation to a larger pattern of continuity and/or change.
*Apply historical thinking skills to topics like the Renaissance, Reformation, Exploration, Scientific and Philosophical Developments, Political Revolutions, War and Ideology.
*Analyze how changes in beliefs about the nature of the state and people‚Äôs relationship to it led to revolution and reform in Eastern and Western Europe.
*Develop arguments about the following themes in European History:
- Interaction of Europe and the World
- Commercial Developments
- Cultural and Intellectual Developments
- States and Other Institutions of Power
- Social Organization and Development
- National and European Identity
- Technological and Scientific Innovation

title: Artificial Intelligence
description:
In 20 episodes, Jabril will teach you about Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning! This course is based on a university-level curriculum. By the end of the course, you will be able to: 

* Define, differentiate, and provide examples of Artificial Intelligence and three types of Machine Learning: supervised, unsupervised, and reinforcement
* Understand how different AI and ML approaches can be combined to create compelling applications such as natural language processing, robotics, recommender systems, and web search
* Implement several types of AI to classify images, generate text from examples, play video games, and recommend content based on past preferences
* Understand the causes of algorithmic bias and audit datasets for several of these causes
* Reason about how specific advances in AI may impact our world and your life, for better or for worse

title: Business Entrepreneurship
description:
In 17 episodes, Anna Akana will teach you entrepreneurship skills to help you start and run a small business. This course is based on a college-level curriculum with a variety of reference texts, including the Strategyzer Business Model Canvas. By the end of the course, you will be able to:

* Evaluate the quality of an idea and take steps to turn it into a small business
* Understand the legal basics of business entity formation, sales, costs, and other finances
* Develop a clear value proposition for your business and customer relationships
* Navigate other businesses, including both competition and key partners 
* Define success for yourself as an entrepreneur, and recognize failure

title: Literature 2
description:
In 16 episodes, John Green discusses more literature! The analyses and books chosen in this course are based on introductory college-level curriculum and the AP Literature guidelines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Use characters and setting to explore a range of values, beliefs, assumptions, biases, and cultural norms
*Discuss the role of the narrator and how their perspective affects how readers experience and interpret a text
*Recognize comparisons, representations, and associations that invite readers to interpret a text
*Explain the function of significant events in a plot, as well as the contributions of structure, sequence, contrast, and conflict
*Employ different lenses and focal points to read a text multiple ways and recognize the glorious ambiguity of literature
*Discuss how different texts explore the themes of mortal and divine justice, and the perpetual cycle of violence

title: Literature 4
description:
In 12 episodes, John Green is back to talk about books. That‚Äôs right, more Crash Course Literature! The analyses and books chosen in this course are based on introductory college-level curriculum and the AP Literature guidelines. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

*Use characters and setting to explore a range of values, beliefs, assumptions, biases, and cultural norms
*Discuss the role of the narrator and how their perspective affects how readers experience and interpret a text
*Recognize comparisons, representations, and associations that invite readers to interpret a text
*Explain the function of significant events in a plot, as well as the contributions of structure, sequence, contrast, and conflict
*Employ different lenses and focal points to read a text multiple ways and recognize the glorious ambiguity of literature
*Question the notion of genre and place, in particular dystopias, and their impact on free will and politics

title: Organic Chemistry
description:
In 50 episodes, Dr. Deboki Chakravarti will teach you organic chemistry. This course is based on sophomore-level college material, covering topics from Organic Chemistry I and II. It was developed with 9 reference texts and journal articles on specialized topics in organic chemistry, in particular: Organic Chemistry texts by Brown, Foote, Iverson and Ansyln (8th ed.); Clayden, Greeves and Warren (2nd ed.); McMurry (9th ed.) By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Recognize and name the major functional groups in organic compounds
* Understand the influence of molecular structure and conformation on chemical properties and reactivity
* Identify the possible reactions for a given organic compound and select reasonable reaction mechanisms given the reactant structure and functional groups
* Sketch a mechanism for an organic reaction, showing valid arrow-pushing and formal charges
* Develop and compare synthetic routes to a target molecule from a starting compound
* Interpret spectra (e.g. IR, NMR, MS, UV/vis) and understand how they are used in structure determination
* Connect the chemical properties of organic compounds to their real-world applications (e.g. in polymers, medicine, and biochemistry).

title: Big History 2
description:
In 6 episodes, Emily Graslie continues telling you the story of ‚Äúlife, the universe, and everything‚Äù in Big History 2! This course challenges you to ask ‚Äúwhy this stuff matters‚Äù and is based on the Big History Project social studies curriculum. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

‚Ä¢Integrate physics, math, history, and more to tell a single story about people, civilizations, and how we are connected to everything around us
‚Ä¢Zoom out to pose and refine scientific and historical questions
‚Ä¢Outline the most powerful and important breakthroughs
‚Ä¢Evaluate how we know what we know and why we‚Äôre sure we know it
‚Ä¢Relate topics in Big History to contemporary humans and describe why they matter in our daily lives

title: Linguistics
description:
In 16 episodes, Taylor Behnke teaches you linguistics! The content is based on an introductory university-level curriculum, curated by a team of linguists: Lauren Gawne, Jessi Grieser, and Gretchen McCulloch. By the end of this course, you will be able to:

* Understand how linguists approach analyzing language, including our ethical responsibility to use our increased understanding of how language works to be more compassionate with language 
* Identify and analyze the structural features of language, across different levels, including phonetics, phonology, morphology, syntax, semantics and pragmatics
* Apply this structural approach to describe language as it is used, including its social functions, how people learn language, and how language is used in technology
* Recognize that there are thousands of spoken languages and hundreds of signed languages in the world 
* Identify the International Phonetic Alphabet and understand the system behind how the IPA chart is organized

title: Geography
description: Welcome to Crash Course Geography hosted by Aliz√© Carr√®re! This 50-episode course will be split into two parts. In the first half, we will focus on physical geography or the processes and phenomena of the physical world both above and below the Earth's surface. We'll ask questions like, "why is the seafloor so young when the Earth is so old?" or try to identify why winds and ocean currents are so important to life on Earth. Then we'll turn our focus to human geography and explore the ways people occupy the Earth's surface. Like how we've moved, settled, and used the land, resources, and space. Join us as we tell the story of the Earth.

title: Zoology
description:
In 14 episodes, Dr. Rae Wynn Grant teaches you zoology! By the end of this series, learners will be able to:
*Describe the main branches of animal life, and the traits that unite/define them
*Analyze representations of evolutionary relatedness 
*Explain the types of evidence used to discover the evolutionary relationships between animals
*Hypothesize about the selective pressures that may have led to evolution of an animal‚Äôs traits and behaviors
*Describe modern-day careers in zoology

title: Crash Course Black American History
description: Over the course of 51 episodes, we're going to learn about Black American History. Clint Smith will teach you about the experience of Black people in America, from the arrival of the first enslaved Black people who arrived at Jamestown all the way to the Black Lives Matter movement.

title: Outbreak Science
description: Welcome to Crash Course Outbreak Science! What do pathogens actually do to us that makes us sick? Why do societies respond to outbreaks of infectious diseases the way they do? How can we stop the next outbreak? These are the kinds of questions we'll ask ourselves and answer as best we can in this 15-episode series. Join us and Dr. Pardis Sabeti as we look at outbreaks from the microscopic level, to the big picture, so that we can work together to stop future outbreaks and create a healthier future for everyone.

title: How to College
description:
Welcome to Crash Course: How to College! This 15 episode series is part of the Study Hall Program; a partnership between Crash Course and ASU. Dr. Erica Brozovsky (from PBS's Otherwords) hosts and breaks down how to apply for, succeed at, and graduate from college.

Study Hall now has online courses that are eligible for college credit! Sign up at https://link.gostudyhall.com/my1

title: Office Hours
description: Getting ready for finals season? Crash Course Office Hours will help you prepare for your Anatomy & Physiology, Geography, and World History exams!

title: Public Health
description:
In 10 episodes, Vanessa Hill teaches you about Public Health! By the end of this series, learners will understand:

*What is public health, and how is it different from medicine?
*Who is involved in public health? 
*What are some of the biological, environmental, and social determinants of health?
*What is epidemiology?
*What are some different kind of healthcare systems and how do they work?
*How are public policy and public health related?
*What could the future of public health look like?

title: Back to School - Expanded
description: Need a quick refresh before going back to school? We've compiled videos from across our many series to help you prepare for a new school year. Chemistry, biology, physics, statistics, literature, philosophy, study skills, and more -- it's all right here!

title: Back to School - Essentials
description: If you only have time for a few videos, this collection will give you a quick refresh before going back to school,

title: Climate & Energy
description:
In 12 episodes, this series covers the evidence and science behind our understanding of climate change. By the end of this course, learners will be able to: 

*Understand the greenhouse effect and the role that greenhouse gas emissions play in climate change
*Identify the five major categories of greenhouse gas emissions/energy sources
*Describe existing decarbonization solutions and identify areas where future innovations are needed
*Explain the current and future impacts of climate change and how they affect different communities
*Describe the political, social, and economic forces that complicate the path to carbon neutrality

title: Environmental Science
description: This playlist features videos from several series that complement our Climate & Energy series, providing context and more in-depth information on specific topics.

title: Botany
description:
Over the course of 15 episodes, we‚Äôre going to learn about botany‚Äîthe study of plants. Alexis Nikole Nelson will teach you about how plants evolved, how they function, and just how vital they are to human societies and all of life on Earth. 

This content is based on an introductory university-level curriculum. By the end of this course, you should be able to: 
*Describe the evolutionary history of plants
*List and describe fundamental anatomical and morphological characteristics of plants
*Understand what plant hormones are and how they work
*Explain what roles plants play in ecosystems and why they are important
*Understand how plant genes play an important role in the diversity of plants we see on Earth
*Understand why plants are important, and how botanical knowledge can be useful in everyday life

title: Biology
description:
In 50 episodes, we‚Äôre going to explore biology‚Äîthe science of life. Dr. Samuel Ramsey will guide you through life‚Äôs vast interconnectedness, telling lesser-known stories of biologists along the way. We‚Äôll discover how evolution, genetics, ecology, and cell and organismal biology deepen our knowledge of every living thing: including ourselves.

This course is based on an introductory-level college and AP Biology curriculum. By the end of this course, you will be able to: 

*Understand what life is and the natural systems that make it possible.
*Describe the types of questions biologists answer and the skills they need to answer them.
*Explain how life is organized in nested systems that regulate biological activities.
*Describe how life on earth has evolved, including the forces driving that change.
*Identify ways in which all of life is interconnected and how biology impacts human society.
*Use scientific language inclusively and accurately.
*Understand the collective nature of biology through examples of innovation and discovery from a wide variety of researchers, civilizations, and cultures, including historically underrepresented scientists and stories

Biology textbooks cited include: Taylor, Simon, Dickey, Hogan and Reece (2017); Morris et al. (2019); Clark, Choi, and Douglas; Murray, Cain, Wassherman, Minorsky, & Reece (2016); and Miller and Levine (2019).

Check out our new channel, Crash Course en Espa√±ol, to watch Crash Course Biolog√≠a!

title: Crash Course for Spooky Season
description: Spooky season is here, and we‚Äôve got just the thing to give you the heebie jeebies. Check out our playlist of Crash Course‚Äôs creepiest videos to get in the Halloween spirit.

title: Crash Course At The Movies
description: Lights, camera, action! We're rolling on the best Crash Course videos about one of our favorite pastimes: movies! Learn about the nuts and bolts behind movie magic, media portrayals of adolescence, how Netflix decides which movies to recommend to you, and what the film industry looks like in different parts of the world.

title: Art History
description: Over the course of 22 episodes, we‚Äôre going to learn about art history‚Äîthe study of objects and images to understand their meaning and the people, places, and times they come from. Sarah Urist Green will equip you with a toolbox of terms to analyze and evaluate art, draw connections between different cultures and time periods, and ask big questions about how history gets made. This content is partially based on the AP Art History curriculum and that of an introductory university-level course. By the end of this series, you should be able to: *Recognize and understand the context of visual/material culture from prehistory to the present*Use the context of a wide array of voices from many different regions to analyze art and provide a nuanced interpretation of material culture*Understand the interconnectedness of global cultures by examining overlapping themes, materials, and technique*Grasp the ways 20th and 21st century art have ushered in, and continue to pave the way for, subsequent movements, as well as advancing contemporary themes, issues, and debates in art history*Use tools and vocabulary to apply what you have learned in the series to art and design in your daily lifeKey texts cited include: Art History Volume 1, 6th edition by Marilyn Stokstad and Michael W. Cothren (2018), Art History Volume 2, 6th edition by Marilyn Stokstad and Michael W. Cothren (2018), Smarthistory: Reframing Art History, edited by Dr. Lauren Kilroy-Ewbank.

title: Crash Course Pods: The Universe
description:
Dr. Katie Mack, a theoretical astrophysicist, walks #1 New York Times bestselling author John Green through the history of the entire universe - including the parts that haven‚Äôt been written yet.

Episodes will be released every two weeks, starting April 24, 2024.

title: Religions
description: John Green teaches you about Religions!

title: Political Theory
description: Over the next 13 episodes, Ellie Anderson will introduce you to the perspectives of political thinkers past and present, and explore how political theories apply to the most burning questions of our time. We‚Äôll compare arguments, trace the origins of contemporary theories, and develop the skills to discuss, disagree, and decide what we want society to be.

title: Presidents and the Presidency of the United States
description: Happy Presidents Day! Use your day off to learn about the US presidency with Crash Course!

title: Women's History Highlights
description: For Women's History Month and beyond, we're highlighting some key stories and accomplishments made by women throughout the ages. With this playlist, your students can learn about major milestones and concepts found throughout women's history (and don't worry if you learn a little something, too‚Äîwe won't tell anyone).

title: Sex Ed
description:
Welcome to Crash Course Sex Ed! Over the course of 15 episodes, sexologist Shan Boodram will introduce you to the surprising, fascinating, wildly diverse, utterly normal realm of human sexuality. This series will explore the many dimensions of sex‚Äîfrom your body, to your personal identity, to the society around you‚Äîso you have the facts you need to make the right choices for you.

By the end of this course, you will be able to:
- Reflect on the ways society shapes our understanding of sex, sexuality, and bodily autonomy
- Explain the functions of anatomy in terms of both reproduction and sexual response
 - Describe the differences between sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, and gender expression, and how our understanding of these aspects of identity continues to evolve 
- Think critically about how sexual consent is communicated
- Describe how unintended pregnancy and STIs can be prevented
- Explore how we identify ourselves and others as sexual beings

title: Native American History
description:
"Welcome to Crash Course Native American History! Over the next 24 episodes, Che Jim will introduce you to the deep, ongoing history of the Indigenous peoples who‚Äôve called these lands home from time immemorial to today.  

Course Description:
Over the course of 24 episodes, we‚Äôre going to learn about Native American history. Host Che Jim will teach you about the deep, ongoing history of Native peoples in what‚Äôs now known as the United States‚Äîfrom time immemorial to the Land Back movement.

This content was developed with a team of Indigenous experts, and based on an introductory college-level curriculum. By the end of this course you should be able to:
- Analyze the political and legal relationship between Native nations and the U.S. government
- Develop an informed perspective on distinct Native cultures‚Äô traditions, practices, and worldview 
- Draw connections between the past and present, in the continued existence and experiences of Native individuals and Native nations
- Highlight key figures in Native American history and illustrate their achievements and contributions

title: CC Latin America Extra Curricular
description: Want to dive deeper into the topics covered in Crash Course Latin American Literature? Then this playlist is for you. Learn more about the geopolitical history of Latin America, the scientific achievements of Indigenous peoples from the region, and the influential forces of migration and borders. Plus, get the full low-down on Gabriel Garc√≠a M√°rquez's masterpiece, "One Hundred Years of Solitude."

title: Crash Course Latin American Literature
description:
In 13 episodes, host Curly Velasquez will introduce you to Latin American Literature! This course is based on sources and topics explored in AP and college-level surveys. By the end of this series, you will be able to:
- Trace major trends and tropes in Latin American literature across genres
- Engage with diverse case studies through a transnational and historical lens
- Identify major periods of Latin American literary history and the debates they raise
- Think critically about the interconnectedness of history, politics, culture, and literature
- Become familiar with prominent, canonical works and marginalized voices in Latin American literature

title: Futures of AI Mini-Series
description:
Welcome to Crash Course: Futures of AI! Our host Kousha Navidar is here to guide you through the ins and outs of our potential AI futures. 

AI is changing FAST so rather than doing a full Crash Course series of 12+ episodes, we‚Äôve prepared a mini-series of just the basics. Crash Course will never tell you what to think and we‚Äôre not the type of organization that responds to breaking news in real time. Instead, we‚Äôre here to offer a zoomed-out foundation upon which to base your own opinions as you continue to learn from other outlets about the world that‚Äôs changing around us.

Crash Course: Futures of AI will cover:
-What even is AI? What‚Äôs the history of this thing and how quickly has it evolved to what exists today?
-How could AI transform society? Will AI cause the next Industrial Revolution, and what might that mean for workers and the environment?
-How powerful could AI become? How do we measure the progression of AI? What are the consequences we‚Äôre already seeing, and what might be the future consequences of unchecked AI development?
-How might powerful AI cause harm? We‚Äôll touch on misinformation, surveillance, authoritarianism, and (unfortunately,) more. 
-How could AI be governed? What are the potential approaches for controlling AI both nationally and internationally?

P.S. Wondering if we used AI to create this series? Nope! Every Complexly video is lovingly, painstakingly human-made.

The Power System is the backbone of electrical engineering - enabling the generation, transmission, and distribution of electrical energy efficiently and reliably. Understanding its concepts is crucial for anyone aspiring to build a career in power engineering, energy systems, or electrical design.
This comprehensive course on Power Systems provides an in-depth understanding of how electrical power is produced, transmitted, and controlled across networks. From power generation methods and economic load dispatch to fault analysis, protection systems, and modern HVDC & FACTS technologies, this course covers every essential aspect of the electrical power system.
Whether you‚Äôre an Electronics or Electrical Engineering student, a competitive exam aspirant (GATE, UGC NET, etc.), or an early-career professional seeking to strengthen your knowledge base, this course is designed to help you develop a strong theoretical foundation and practical insights into modern power systems.

This field is undergoing rapid change, as computers are now prevalent in virtually every application. Yet the fundamental concepts remain fairly clear and that is what will be taught in this course.
In brief, an operating system acts as an intermediary between the user of a computer and the computer hardware. The purpose of an operating system is to provide an environment in which a user can execute programs in a convenient and efficient manner. 
Every important aspects of an Operating System will be taught in this course so as to get a proper understanding about Operating Systems and their design and working.

title: Fourier Series | Chapter 6 | Signals and Systems
description:
This comprehensive video playlist on Fourier Series is part of the Signals and Systems course, meticulously designed for engineering students (especially in Computer Science, Electronics, and Electrical Engineering), GATE, UGC NET, IES, and other competitive exam aspirants, as well as early-career professionals seeking strong fundamentals in signal analysis.
Fourier Series is a cornerstone topic in signal processing, control systems, and communications. It enables the analysis of periodic signals by decomposing them into sinusoids‚Äîproviding the basis for frequency-domain analysis. This series begins with intuitive introductions and dives deep into the Dirichlet conditions, Trigonometric and Complex Exponential Fourier Series, and various properties and symmetries used in solving real-world signal processing problems.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Introduction to Fourier Series - Understand the motivation, applications, and basic concepts behind Fourier Series.
2. Conditions for Existence of Fourier Series (Dirichlet Conditions) - Learn the three mathematical conditions a periodic signal must satisfy for a valid Fourier Series.
3. Trigonometric Fourier Series - Detailed explanation of trigonometric expansion and coefficient formulas for periodic signals.
4. Trigonometric Fourier Series (Example 1) - Solve a rectangular wave problem and find its Fourier coefficients.
5. Trigonometric Fourier Series (Example 2) - Analyze a sawtooth wave using the trigonometric Fourier Series.
6. Trigonometric Fourier Series (Example 3) - Previous year IES-2011 and GATE-2002 questions on Fourier expansion solved.
7. Trigonometric Fourier Series (Example 4) - Solve and analyze GATE-2006 and GATE-2011 problems.
8. Trigonometric Fourier Series (Example 5) - Additional problem-solving on Fourier Series using trigonometric approach.
9. Complex Exponential Fourier Series - Learn the exponential form, coefficient calculation, and symmetry properties.
10. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Example 1) - Solve a numerical problem using exponential form of Fourier Series.
11. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Example 2) - Solve a GATE-1999 question using exponential coefficients.
12. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Example 3) - Compute the Fourier coefficient C‚Çô from the signal.
13. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Example 4) - Reconstruct the signal from given Fourier coefficients.
14. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Example 5) - Analyze a signal from magnitude and phase plots of C‚Çô.
15. Relation between Fourier Coefficients - Explore how trigonometric and exponential coefficients relate to each other.
16. Relation between Fourier Coefficients (Solved Problem) - Convert complex exponential coefficients to trigonometric form through examples.
17. x(t)‚àíCn Pairs (Shortcut for Objectives) - Common signal‚Äìcoefficient pairs and proofs, useful for objective-type questions.
18. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Solved MCQ 1) - Fast MCQ solution using x(t)‚ÄìC‚Çô shortcuts.
19. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Solved MCQ 2) - Identify signal characteristics from given Fourier coefficients.
20. Complex Exponential Fourier Series (Solved MCQ 3) - More MCQs based on exponential form properties.
21. Symmetricities in Fourier Series (Part 1) - Understand even, odd, and half-wave symmetry and their impact on coefficients.
22. Symmetricities in Fourier Series (Part 2) - Explore combined and hidden symmetry types in Fourier Series.
23. Hidden Symmetry in Fourier Series (Examples) - Solve problems that reveal hidden symmetries to simplify calculations.
24. Properties of Fourier Series (Part 1) - Linearity and conjugation properties explained with examples.
25. Properties of Fourier Series (Part 2) - Time-reversal and scaling properties of Fourier coefficients.
26. Properties of Fourier Series (Part 3) - Understand time-shifting and frequency-shifting in the frequency domain.
27. Properties of Fourier Series (Part 4) - Learn how convolution in time affects Fourier coefficients.
28. Properties of Fourier Series (Part 5) - Analyze effects of signal multiplication in time domain on coefficients.
29. Properties of Fourier Series (Part 6) - Learn differentiation and integration effects on Fourier coefficients.
30. Parseval's Power Theorem - Theoretical foundation and derivation of power distribution in Fourier domain.
31. Parseval's Power Theorem (Solved Example) - Apply the theorem to solve power-based problems.
32. Properties of Fourier Series (Solved Problems) - Solve coefficient-based problems using known Fourier properties.
33. Fourier Series for LTI Systems - Understand how periodic inputs behave through LTI systems and how output coefficients are derived.

title: Fourier Transform | Chapter 7 | Signals and Systems
description:
This comprehensive playlist delves into Fourier Transform from the subject Signals and Systems, essential for understanding signal analysis in both time and frequency domains. Whether you're a Computer Science, Electronics, or Electrical Engineering student, preparing for competitive exams like GATE, ESE (IES), UGC NET, or looking to solidify your fundamentals as an early-career professional, this series is designed to build conceptual clarity through in-depth explanations and solved problems.

9. Recursion (Solved Problem 4) - GATE 2015 solved problem on recursion.

title: Arrays & Pointers in C
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive exploration of arrays and pointers in C programming, covering fundamental concepts, advanced techniques, and competitive exam-level problem solving. Learn about one-dimensional, two-dimensional, and three-dimensional arrays, including their declaration, initialization, accessing elements, and memory management. Dive deep into pointer basics, pointer arithmetic, pointer assignments, and advanced pointer applications like passing arrays to functions, returning pointers, and pointers to entire arrays.
With GATE-level solved problems and practical programs, this playlist is ideal for students, competitive exam aspirants (GATE, UGC NET), and early-career professionals seeking mastery of arrays, pointers, and multidimensional array handling in C.
This playlist is ideal for Computer Science students looking to master arrays and pointers in C, competitive exam aspirants preparing for GATE, UGC NET, and similar exams, early-career programmers seeking to strengthen their C programming fundamentals and advanced pointer applications.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Definition of Array - Introduction to arrays, one-dimensional arrays, and examples.
2. Declaration of Array - Syntax, declaration, and length of one-dimensional arrays.

15. Constant Arrays in C - Benefits and examples of constant arrays.
16. Variable Length Arrays in C - Concepts, examples, and advantages of variable-length arrays.
17. Introduction to Pointers in C - Pointer definition and basic examples.
18. Declaring & Initializing Pointers in C - Declaration, initialization, and use of the address-of operator.
19. Value of Operator in Pointers - Using dereferencing to access pointer values.
20. Pointer Assignment - Assigning pointer content and comparing q = p vs *q = *p.

33. Processing the Multidimensional Array Elements (or Address Arithmetic of Multidimensional Arrays) - Process 1D, 2D, and 3D arrays using pointers.
34. Pointers (Program 3) - Solved GATE 2002 pointer problem.
35. Pointers (Program 4) - Solved GATE 2015 pointer problem.
36. Pointer Pointing to an Entire Array - Explains pointers pointing to the whole array.
37. Pointer Pointing to an Entire Array (Solved Problem) - Example problem and solution.

39. Pointers (Program 6) - Solved GATE 2010 (2 Marks) pointer problem.
40. Pointers (Program 7) - Solved GATE 2008 (2 Marks) pointer problem.
41. Pointers (Program 8) - Solved GATE 2006 (2 Marks) pointer problem.
42. Pointers (Program 9) - Additional solved problem on pointers in C.

title: Strings in C
description:
This playlist provides a comprehensive understanding of Strings in C Programming, covering everything from the fundamentals of string literals to advanced string operations and memory management. Learn how to declare, initialize, and manipulate strings, utilize standard C string library functions such as strcpy, strlen, strcat, strncat, and strcmp, and explore arrays of strings for handling multiple text inputs efficiently.
The playlist also includes GATE-level solved problems on strings, helping competitive exam aspirants understand real-world applications of string handling in C. Additionally, the final lecture introduces function pointers, illustrating their role in storing and calling functions dynamically. This series is ideal for students, competitive exam aspirants (GATE, UGC NET), and early-career programmers looking to strengthen their grasp of C strings and pointers.
This playlist is ideal for Computer Science students looking to master string handling in C, competitive exam aspirants preparing for GATE, UGC NET, and other technical exams, early-career programmers seeking to strengthen their understanding of C strings, pointers, and function pointers.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Basics of String Literals - Introduction to string literals in C, including definition, examples, and continuation across lines.
2. Storing the String Literals - Explains how string literals are stored in memory and accessed efficiently.
3. Performing Operations on String Literals - Demonstrates using pointers and subscripting to manipulate string literals.
4. String Literal vs. Character Constant - Highlights the differences and shows how to pass them to printf.
5. Declaring and Initializing String Variables - Covers different initialization methods, including short, long, and equal length initializers.
6. Writing Strings using printf and puts Functions - Shows how to print full strings, parts of strings, and right-justified text.
7. Reading Strings using scanf and gets Functions - Explains string input using scanf and gets.
8. Designing The Input Function using getchar() - Step-by-step guide to creating a custom input function using getchar().
9. putchar() Function in C - Introduces putchar() function, its prototype, usage, and examples.
10. Strings (Solved Problem 1) - Solved question on strings to understand practical usage.
11. C String Library and String Copy Function-strcpy() - Introduction to the C string library and strcpy/strncpy functions with examples.
12. String Length Function-strlen() - Explains how to use strlen() to determine string length.
13. String Concatenate Functions-strcat() & strncat() - Demonstrates concatenating strings using standard library functions.
14. String Comparison Function-strcmp() - Covers strcmp() function and ASCII considerations for string comparison.
15. Array of Strings - How to store and manage multiple strings using 2D arrays and pointer arrays.
16. Strings (Solved Problem 2) - GATE CS 2004 solved problem on strings in C.
17. Strings (Solved Problem 3) - GATE CS 2011 solved problem illustrating string operations.
18. Strings (Solved Problem 4) - GATE CS 2015 solved question on strings for practice.
19. Strings (Solved Problem 5) - GATE CS 2018 solved problem demonstrating advanced string handling.
20. Strings (Solved Problem 6) - GATE CS 2017 solved question for competitive exam preparation.
21. Function Pointers in C - Introduction to function pointers, their declaration, calling functions dynamically, and example applications.

title: Structure & Union in C
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive and concept-driven exploration of Structures and Unions in C Programming, two of the most important topics in understanding memory management, data organization, and efficient coding in C. From defining and declaring structures to structure padding, packing, unions, and enumerations, every concept is covered in a clear, example-oriented manner.
The playlist combines theory and practice - with step-by-step explanations, GATE (CS) solved problems, and real-world applications - making it perfect for learners aiming to master C Programming at an academic and professional level.
This series is ideal for Computer Science students learning C Programming fundamentals, GATE, UGC NET, and university exam aspirants, early-career programmers and software engineers preparing for interviews, anyone seeking to strengthen their understanding of data representation and memory layout in C.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Introduction to Structures in C - Explains what structures are, why they are needed, and how they enhance modular programming in C.
2. Declaring Structure Variables - Covers how to declare and define structure variables for practical data organization.
3. Structure Types (Using Structure Tags) - Introduces structure tags and their use in defining reusable structure types.
4. Structure Types (Using typedef) - Demonstrates how typedef simplifies structure declarations and improves code readability.
5. Initializing & Accessing the Structure Members - Explains different methods to initialize and access members of a structure in C.
6. Designated Initialization in Structures - Introduces designated initialization and its role in improving code clarity.
7. Declaring an Array of Structure - Shows how to handle multiple data entries using arrays of structures.
8. Pointer to Structure Variable - Discusses pointer usage with structures and accessing members via pointers.
9. Structure Padding in C - Explains memory alignment, structure padding, and how compilers optimize data storage.
10. Structure Packing in C - Covers how to disable padding and pack structures efficiently in memory.
11. Structures in C (Solved Problem 1) - A basic solved problem demonstrating structure declaration and member access.
12. Structures in C (Solved Problem 2) - GATE CS 2018 solved question focusing on memory and structure manipulation.
13. Structures in C (Solved Problem 3) - GATE CS 2000 solved problem illustrating structure size and member relationships.
14. Introduction to Unions in C - Explains the concept of unions, their memory-sharing mechanism, and practical usage.
15. Unions in C (Solved Problem 1) - Solution to a GATE 2000 problem on Unions highlighting size and member access.
16. Application of Unions (Part 1) - Demonstrates practical applications of Unions with real C examples.
17. Application of Unions (Part 2) - Shows how to create mixed data types using unions effectively.
18. Enumerations in C - Discusses the definition, need, and use of enums for improving program readability.
19. Program to Find Area of Rectangle Using Structures - A simple C program that demonstrates structure-based problem-solving.
20. Structures & Unions in C (Solved Problem) - Final problem-solving video combining concepts of both Structures and Unions in practical scenarios.

title: Computer Networks
description:
Computer networking impacts almost all aspects of our lives. Computer networks support the way we learn, communicate, play and work. Computer networking is an ever-evolving field with new technological advancements; network management can be a fun, exciting, and rewarding career path. Computer network administrators and security professionals are the ones who make sure computer systems run smoothly and seamlessly. They can install operating systems, configure networks and network management protocols, and manage network security. In this course, the fundamentals, protocols, and advanced networking concepts are dealt simply, deeply, and precisely. Understanding computer networking with OS-based networking commands, simulations using Cisco packet tracer and Wireshark packet sniffing tools are always engrossing and make learning interesting. The learner will find the following topics.

1. Fundamentals
    1.1 Basic Characteristics of Computer Network.
    1.2 Network Protocols and Communication.
    1.3 Components of a computer network.
    1.4 Classification of Computer Network: 
           LAN, WAN, MAN, and SAN.
    1.5 Network Topology: Bus, Star, Ring, Mesh, Hybrid.
    1.6 Network Devices: Router, Switch, HUB, Bridge.
    1.7 Circuit Switching vs Packet Switching networks.
    1.8 The OSI Reference Model.
    1.9 TCP/IP Model.

2. Data Link Layer
    2.1 Link Layer services.
    2.2 Framing.
    2.3 Flow Control.
    2.4 Error Detection and Error Control.
    2.5 Media Access Control.
    2.6 Ethernet(IEEE 802.3), Wi-Fi (IEEE 802.11) and 
           Bluetooth (IEEE 802.15).
    2.7 Switching and Bridging.
    2.8 Spanning Tree Protocol (STP).

3. Network Layer
    3.1 IP protocol and IP address: Public and Private.
    3.2 Classful addressing versus classless addressing.
    3.3 Subnetting and CIDR.
    3.4 Static and Dynamic Routing.
    3.5 Distance Vector ‚Äì RIP.
    3.6 Link State Routing ‚Äì OSPF.
    3.7 BGP and EIGRP.
    3.8 Network Address Translation (NAT).
    3.9 Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).
    3.10 IPV6.

4. Transport Layer
    4.1 User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
    4.2 Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
    4.3 TCP Connection establishment and termination.
    4.4 Flow control.
    4.5 Retransmission.
    4.6 TCP Congestion control.
    4.7 Congestion avoidance.
    4.8 Quality of Service (QoS).

5. Application Layer
    5.1 Electronic mail protocols: SMTP, POP3, and IMAP.
    5.2 HyperText Transfer Protocol (HTTP).
    5.3 Domain Name System (DNS).
    5.4 Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP).

6. Network Security
    6.1 Security Threats and Attacks.
    6.2 The OSI security architecture.
    6.3 Cryptography.
    6.4 Public key and Private key Cryptography.
    6.5 Malicious software.

title: Java Programming
description:
In this course, you will learn to program using the Java programming language. You will learn how to think like a programmer and how to solve complex problems by developing programs. This course is for everyone including beginners and experienced developers. We will give you all the concepts and all the skills you need to be a powerful programmer. Java is a very powerful and popular programming language, if you learn it now this will be a great addition to your cv and your skillset.

SYLLABUS:
1. Introduction to Programming & Java.
     a. Programs.
     b. Programming Languages.
     c. Java Program Anatomy.
     d. Compiling and executing a program.
     e. Java Packages, Classes, & methods.
     f. Programming Styles.
    g. Programming Errors.
    h. Typing Faster.

2. Variables and Data Types in Java.
    a. Variables.
    b. Data Types.
    d. Instantiating Objects.

    e. Break and Continue.

6. Methods in Java.
    a. Defining Methods.
    b. Calling Methods.
    c. Return Types. 
    d. Passing Parameters by Value.
    e. Overloading Methods.
    f. The Scope of Variables.

7. Single-Dimensional Arrays.
    a. Array Basics.
    b. Passing Arrays to Methods.
    c. Returning an Array from a Method.

8. Multidimensional Arrays.
    a. Two-Dimensional Arrays Basics.
    b. Passing 2D Arrays to Methods.
    c. Multidimensional Arrays.

title: Network Theorems | Chapter 4 | Network Theory
description:
This playlist provides a comprehensive guide to Network Theorems, a crucial topic in Electrical Engineering, Electronics, and Computer Science. Understanding theorems such as Superposition, Thevenin‚Äôs, Norton‚Äôs, Reciprocity, Millman‚Äôs, Compensation, Substitution, Tellegen‚Äôs, and Maximum Power Transfer is essential for circuit analysis and forms a strong foundation for advanced studies in signal processing, communications, and power systems.
This structured playlist is aligned with engineering curriculum, competitive exams (GATE, ESE, IES, UGC NET), and professional skill-building, ensuring learners can apply these concepts to both academic success and practical circuit design.
