The videos guide you through the fundamentals of pointer operations with practical examples, conceptual explanations, and homework problems to reinforce learning.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Pointer Arithmetic (Addition) - Learn how to add integers to pointers, how pointer offsets work in memory, and practice with a homework problem on pointer arithmetic.
2. Pointer Arithmetic (Subtraction) - Understand how subtracting integers or one pointer from another works in C. Includes discussion on undefined behaviors and best practices.
3. Pointer Arithmetic (Increment & Decrement) - Explore pre- and post-increment/decrement operations on pointers, and how they affect pointer values during iteration and memory navigation.
4. Pointer Arithmetic (Comparing the Pointers) - Delve into pointer comparisons using relational and equality operators, with example problems and a conceptual homework task to test your understanding.

title: Pointer Programs in C
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive and practical guide to mastering pointers in C programming through carefully curated solved programs and GATE-level questions. With an emphasis on both conceptual clarity and hands-on coding, it is ideal for students, competitive exam aspirants, and early-career software professionals looking to strengthen their understanding of pointers‚Äîone of the most fundamental and challenging topics in C.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Pointers (Program 1) | Sum of Array Elements using Pointers - Learn how to use pointers to iterate over an array and compute the sum of its elements in C.
2. Pointers (Program 2) | Reversing a Series of Numbers using Pointers - Practice reversing a list of numbers in-place using pointer manipulation.
3. Pointers (Program 3) - Solution to a GATE 2002 question on pointers, demonstrating key concepts like dereferencing and pointer arithmetic.
4. Pointers (Program 4) - A detailed walkthrough of a GATE 2015 pointer question, focusing on how memory access works in C.
5. Pointers (Program 5) - Covers a GATE 2010 question using pointer expressions and array indexing.
6. Pointers (Program 6) - Solve a 2-mark GATE 2010 problem involving nuanced pointer behavior and memory referencing.
7. Pointers (Program 7) - Understand a tricky GATE 2008 (2 Marks) pointer question with a step-by-step solution.
8. Pointers (Program 8) - Go through a GATE 2006 problem on pointers that emphasizes precise memory access and pointer manipulation.
9. Pointers (Program 9) - A general solved problem on pointers in C programming to reinforce core concepts and common pitfalls.

title: Strings in C - Solved Problems
description:
This playlist is a focused collection of solved problems on Strings in C Programming, covering key concepts through GATE Computer Science previous year questions and other hand-picked examples. Strings are an essential part of the C language, often appearing in exams and interviews due to their complexity in memory handling and pointer manipulation. This playlist helps you build a strong grasp of how strings are stored, accessed, and manipulated in C.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Strings (Solved Problem 1) - A solved question on strings in C that introduces key concepts like character arrays and memory layout.
2. Strings (Solved Problem 2) - Solution to a GATE CS 2004 problem on strings, focusing on string declaration and memory behavior.
3. Strings (Solved Problem 3) - Covers a GATE CS 2011 question, analyzing pointer operations and the structure of string literals.
4. Strings (Solved Problem 4) - Explains the logic behind a GATE CS 2015 string-related question, focusing on edge cases with string manipulation.
5. Strings (Solved Problem 5) - Solves a GATE CS 2018 problem, reinforcing how strings interact with loops, functions, and memory.
6. Strings (Solved Problem 6) - A thorough explanation of a GATE CS 2017 question on strings, illustrating practical debugging strategies.

title: Structures in C - Solved Problems
description:
This playlist provides a concise and concept-oriented walkthrough of Structures in C, featuring solved problems from GATE (CS) and other exam-style questions. Structures are a core feature of the C programming language, allowing developers to group related data types, enabling efficient data modeling. In competitive exams and coding interviews, structure-based questions often test understanding of memory layout, padding, pointer access, and nested structures.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Structures in C (Solved Problem 1) - Covers a foundational problem on using structures in C, explaining structure declaration, member access, and related concepts.
2. Structures in C (Solved Problem 2) - A detailed solution to a GATE CS 2018 problem, focusing on structure member access and memory handling.
3. Structures in C (Solved Problem 3) - Breaks down a GATE CS 2000 problem involving structures, highlighting nuances like structure padding and size evaluation.

title: Block Cipher | Chapter 3 | Cryptography & Network Security
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive exploration of Block Ciphers, a crucial concept in Cryptography & Network Security. Designed for Computer Science students, GATE/UGC NET aspirants, and early-career professionals, the content aligns with academic syllabi and competitive exam patterns. Through intuitive explanations, real-world examples, and solved problems, this chapter demystifies how secure communication is achieved through cryptographic algorithms.
Whether you're preparing for an exam or seeking to build strong foundational knowledge in cybersecurity, this playlist will serve as a structured and reliable learning resource.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Stream Cipher vs. Block Cipher - Compares stream and block ciphers in terms of operation, design principles, speed, and encryption techniques, starting with Shannon‚Äôs Confusion and Diffusion concepts.
2. Feistel Cipher Structure - Explains the structure of Feistel Ciphers, their encryption/decryption processes, and key design features like block size, number of rounds, and round functions.
3. Introduction to Data Encryption Standard (DES) - Introduces the DES algorithm, including its block/key size, initial and inverse permutations, and basic encryption structure.
4. Single Round of DES Algorithm - Breaks down one full round of the DES process and introduces the Round Function and its operations.
5. The F Function of DES (Mangler Function) - Explores the critical ‚ÄúF‚Äù function, focusing on substitution and transposition, including examples using S-Boxes and permutation boxes.
6. Key Scheduling and Decryption in DES - Details how the 64-bit key is reduced to 56 bits and how round keys are generated and reversed during decryption.
7. Avalanche Effect and the Strength of DES - Discusses the Avalanche Effect, brute-force attacks, and resistance of DES, Triple DES, and AES against various attacks.
8. Data Encryption Standard (DES) - Solved Questions - Provides five solved examples to solidify understanding of DES operations and its internal mechanisms.
9. Introduction to Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) - Covers AES structure and introduces the main differences from DES in terms of operation, key scheduling, and number of rounds.
10. AES Encryption and Decryption - Explains the AES encryption/decryption process round-by-round and the role of various transformations.
11. AES Round Transformation - Detailed explanation of core AES transformations: Substitute Bytes, Shift Rows, Mix Columns, and Add Round Key.
12. AES Key Expansion - Demonstrates how AES expands round keys using the g-function, S-Box, and round constants.
13. AES Security and Implementation Aspects - Discusses AES‚Äôs historical context, security strengths, implementation concerns, and demonstration tools.
14. Multiple Encryption and Triple DES - Explains the evolution from DES to 3DES, including 2DES, MITM attacks, and drawbacks of multiple encryption schemes.
15. Block Cipher Modes of Operation - Introduces the need for cipher modes to encrypt data larger than a block, covering all five NIST-defined modes.
16. Electronic Codebook (ECB) - Explains ECB with diagrams, outlines its vulnerabilities, and uses image encryption (e.g., penguin image) to demonstrate issues.
17. Cipher Block Chaining (CBC) - Describes CBC operation with diagrams and evaluates its strengths and weaknesses in practical applications.
18. Cipher Feedback (CFB) - Details the CFB mode, illustrating encryption flow and analyzing its pros and cons.
19. Output Feedback (OFB) - Explains OFB operation with diagrams and discusses where it performs well and where it doesn't.
20. Counter Mode (CTR) - Introduces CTR mode, how it generates ciphertext blocks, and its advantages in parallel processing environments.
21. Block Cipher Modes of Operation (Solved Question) - A worked-out example focusing on the CFB mode of operation to reinforce conceptual understanding.
22. Pseudorandom Number Generator (PRNG) - Discusses the significance of randomness in encryption, key stream generation, and perfect secrecy as proposed by Shannon.
23. Golomb‚Äôs Randomness Postulates - Covers fundamental properties like period, runs, and auto-correlation and illustrates Golomb‚Äôs criteria for randomness with examples.

title: OSI Security Architecture
description:
This playlist provides a foundational understanding of the OSI Security Architecture, a critical concept in Cryptography & Network Security. Designed for Computer Science students, GATE/UGC NET aspirants, and early-career cybersecurity professionals, this series helps learners build a conceptual and practical grasp of how security is structured within network communication systems.
This playlist is perfect for anyone looking to prepare for competitive exams like GATE (CSE), UGC NET, or simply wanting to strengthen their foundational knowledge in Network Security, Cybersecurity Architecture, or Information Security Principles.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. The OSI Security Architecture - Introduces the core concepts of threats, attacks, and vulnerabilities, followed by the OSI model‚Äôs security structure, covering attacks, services, and mechanisms.
2. Security Attacks - Explores different types of attacks in detail, including passive (e.g., traffic analysis) and active attacks (e.g., masquerade, replay, DoS), and compares their implications.
3. Security Services - Breaks down the five key security services in the OSI model: Authentication, Access Control, Data Confidentiality, Data Integrity, and Non-repudiation, with real-world examples.
4. Security Mechanisms - Covers both specific mechanisms (e.g., encipherment, digital signatures) and pervasive mechanisms (e.g., event detection, security audit), explaining how they support security services.
5. Network Security Model - Explains the need for a network security model, outlines its four main tasks, and discusses the role of gatekeeper functions in safeguarding systems.

title: Caesar Cipher
description:
This playlist provides an insightful introduction to Classical Encryption Techniques, focusing specifically on the Caesar Cipher, one of the oldest and simplest forms of cryptography. It‚Äôs an essential topic for anyone starting their journey in Network Security or preparing for competitive exams like GATE (CSE), UGC NET, or other Computer Science-related assessments.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Caesar Cipher (Part 1) - Introduces the Caesar Cipher algorithm, its role in classical cryptography, and explains its working through a detailed example.
2. Caesar Cipher (Part 2) - Expands on Shift Ciphers, explains their pros and cons, and introduces brute force cryptanalysis techniques with illustrative examples.

title: Playfair Cipher
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive exploration of the Playfair Cipher, a significant advancement in classical cryptographic techniques. As part of the broader domain of Cryptography & Network Security, this cipher goes beyond simple substitution methods like Caesar and monoalphabetic ciphers by encrypting letter pairs (digrams), making cryptanalysis more complex.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Playfair Cipher (Part 1) - Introduces the Playfair Cipher in the context of classical cryptosystems, explains the construction of the 5x5 matrix using a keyword, and outlines encryption rules with digram preparation.
2. Playfair Cipher (Part 2) - Applies Playfair rules to generate ciphertext, with multiple examples and a rapid-fire activity to reinforce the encryption process.
3. Playfair Cipher (Solved Question) - Demonstrates a full encryption example for the plaintext ‚ÄúHide the gold under the carpet‚Äù using the keyword ‚ÄúNeso Academy‚Äù and presents a decryption challenge for learners.

title: Hill Cipher
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive introduction to the Hill Cipher, a powerful classical encryption technique that combines cryptography with linear algebra. Widely regarded as one of the most mathematically rich classical ciphers, Hill Cipher is based on matrix operations and modular arithmetic concepts that are foundational to modern network security and cryptographic systems.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Hill Cipher (Encryption) - Learn how the Hill Cipher encrypts messages using matrix multiplication. This video introduces the Hill algorithm, demonstrates encryption with a 3x3 matrix for the plaintext ‚ÄúPay more money,‚Äù and explains both row and column vector approaches.
2. Hill Cipher (Decryption) - Dive into the decryption process using Hill Cipher. Topics include key inverse matrix computation, determinant and adjoint calculation, modular inverse, and a detailed decryption example using the ciphertext ‚ÄúRRLMWBKASPDH.‚Äù

title: Polyalphabetic Cipher
description:
This playlist offers a clear and in-depth exploration of polyalphabetic ciphers, a class of classical encryption techniques that significantly improve on monoalphabetic substitution by using multiple cipher alphabets. Focusing on two key systems Vigen√®re Cipher and Vernam Cipher this series unpacks how polyalphabetic techniques enhance the security of plaintext messages and introduces the cryptanalytic challenges they pose.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Polyalphabetic Cipher (Vigen√®re Cipher) - Learn the working principles of the Vigen√®re Cipher, including its comparison with monoalphabetic ciphers, the impact of repeating keys, frequency analysis vulnerabilities, and how the auto-key system improves its security‚Äîcomplete with practical examples.
2. Polyalphabetic Cipher (Vernam Cipher) - Understand the fundamentals of the Vernam Cipher, its working using binary operations, and the significance of key randomness and length. This video also discusses why a perfectly random key makes the cipher theoretically unbreakable and examines its cryptanalytic resilience.

title: Modular Arithmetic & Exponentiation
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive introduction to Modular Arithmetic & Modular Exponentiation, foundational topics in Cryptography & Network Security. These concepts play a crucial role in encryption algorithms like RSA and are essential for anyone aiming to master the mathematics behind secure digital communication.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Modular Arithmetic (Part 1) - Introduces modular arithmetic using a real-life clock analogy, discusses the significance of congruence in cryptography, and shows how to differentiate between valid and invalid congruence examples.
2. Modular Arithmetic (Part 2) - Uses the circle and thread analogy to deepen understanding and explores essential properties of modular arithmetic including commutative, associative, distributive, identity, and inverse properties.
3. Modular Exponentiation (Part 1) - Explains modular exponentiation and walks through problems like 23¬≥ mod 30, 31‚Åµ‚Å∞‚Å∞ mod 30, and 242¬≥¬≤‚Åπ mod 243 using simple and effective shortcut methods.
4. Modular Exponentiation (Part 2) - Continues with practical examples including 88‚Å∑ mod 187, 29‚Åµ (last two digits), and 3¬π‚Å∞‚Å∞ mod 29. Includes a mini-assignment on computing 11¬≤¬≥ mod 187 and the last three digits of 175¬≤‚Å∞‚Åπ.

title: GCD - Euclidean Algorithm
description:
This playlist provides a clear and structured introduction to the concept of Greatest Common Divisor (GCD) or Highest Common Factor (HCF) using both manual methods and the Euclidean Algorithm, a cornerstone technique in number theory and cryptographic computations. Understanding how to compute the GCD efficiently is foundational for learning advanced topics such as modular arithmetic, public key cryptography (e.g., RSA), and algorithm design.
This content is especially beneficial for Computer Science students, competitive exam aspirants, and early-career professionals looking to strengthen their understanding of mathematical foundations in computer science.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. GCD ‚Äì Euclidean Algorithm (Method 1) - Introduces the concepts of divisors and common factors, and demonstrates manual techniques for computing GCD with examples like GCD(12,33), GCD(25,150), and GCD(13,31), before transitioning into the Euclidean Algorithm.
2. GCD ‚Äì Euclidean Algorithm (Method 2) - Continues with a deeper focus on Euclid‚Äôs Algorithm, presenting additional solved examples including GCD(50,12) and GCD(83,19), reinforcing the systematic steps of the method.

title: Euler's Totient Function
description:
This playlist offers a detailed and beginner-friendly introduction to Euler‚Äôs Totient Function (Œ¶ or Phi Function), a core concept in number theory and network security, particularly within RSA cryptography and modular arithmetic. Designed to strengthen your mathematical foundation, these lectures walk you through both basic and advanced techniques to compute Œ¶(n), an essential function used in public-key encryption algorithms and various competitive exams.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Euler‚Äôs Totient Function (Phi Function) - Introduces the concept of Euler‚Äôs Totient Function Œ¶(n), its mathematical significance, and step-by-step methods to compute Œ¶(n) for smaller integers.
2. Euler‚Äôs Totient Function (Solved Examples) - Builds on the basics with in-depth solved examples for larger numbers. Covers special cases where n is a prime, a product of two primes, or includes composite-prime combinations, using efficient formulas.

title: Extended Euclidean Algorithm
description:
This playlist provides a clear and practical understanding of the Extended Euclidean Algorithm, a fundamental concept in number theory and network security, especially when computing the Multiplicative Inverse under modulus, a key operation in algorithms like RSA, modular arithmetic, and cryptographic key generation.
Whether you're looking to strengthen your number theory skills or prepare for technical exams and interviews, this playlist offers the conceptual clarity and hands-on practice needed to master the Extended Euclidean Algorithm.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Extended Euclidean Algorithm (Solved Example 1) - Introduces the concept of the multiplicative inverse under modulus, explains the Extended Euclidean Algorithm, and solves a complete example with detailed steps and verification.
2. Extended Euclidean Algorithm (Solved Example 2) - Focuses on calculating and verifying the multiplicative inverse of 11 mod 13 using the Extended Euclidean Algorithm.
3. Extended Euclidean Algorithm (Solved Example 3) - Demonstrates the process of finding the multiplicative inverse of 11 mod 26, reinforcing the algorithm‚Äôs application to more complex cases.

title: Chinese Remainder Theorem
description:
This playlist offers a deep and practical understanding of the Chinese Remainder Theorem (CRT), a powerful result in number theory that has wide applications in network security, modular arithmetic, and cryptographic systems like RSA. CRT enables efficient computation with large numbers by solving systems of congruent equations with pairwise coprime moduli, making it an essential concept in Computer Science and Cybersecurity.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. The Chinese Remainder Theorem (Solved Example 1) - Introduces the Chinese Remainder Theorem with a complete explanation of its components, followed by a step-by-step solved example using three congruent equations. Also includes guidance on verifying the final result.
2. The Chinese Remainder Theorem (Solved Example 2) - Reinforces CRT concepts through an additional solved problem, helping learners build confidence in applying the theorem to real-world and exam-based problems.

title: Discrete Logarithm Problem
description:
This playlist introduces and explores one of the foundational concepts in modern cryptography ‚Äî the Discrete Logarithm Problem (DLP). Widely used in public-key cryptographic systems such as Diffie-Hellman key exchange, ElGamal encryption, and Elliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC), DLP is a classic example of a one-way function easy to compute in one direction but computationally hard to reverse.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. The Discrete Logarithm Problem - Introduces the concept of the Discrete Logarithm Problem through a relatable analogy, explains how it works with examples, and discusses essential ideas like primitive roots and the one-way function characteristic of DLP.
2. The Discrete Logarithm Problem (Solved Example) - Demonstrates a step-by-step worked-out example based on the Discrete Logarithm Problem to help reinforce the learning and boost confidence in solving similar problems in exams or real-world cryptographic applications.

title: Semiconductor Physics | Chapter 1 | Analog Electronics
description:
This playlist offers a foundational yet in-depth exploration of Semiconductor Physics, specifically curated as Chapter 1 of the Analog Electronics course. Whether you're a Computer Science or Electronics student, an aspirant for competitive exams like GATE, UGC NET, or PSUs, or a beginner in VLSI, embedded systems, or electronic design, this playlist is your go-to guide for mastering the core concepts of semiconductors.
The content is aligned with academic syllabi and exam patterns, making it ideal for self-paced learning, exam revision, or concept strengthening. The delivery is clear, precise, and suited to both beginners and those looking to reinforce their basics.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Semiconductor Materials - Introduces the difference between conductors, insulators, and semiconductors, resistivity, and energy-band diagrams with a look into the atomic structure of silicon.
2. Intrinsic and Extrinsic Semiconductors - Covers the key differences between intrinsic and extrinsic semiconductors, including types like n-type and p-type materials.
3. Electron Vs Hole Flow - Explains the two types of charge carriers in semiconductors and compares the flow of electrons versus holes in various scenarios.
4. Mass Action Law - Discusses properties of silicon and germanium, the derivation and proof of the Mass Action Law in semiconductor physics.
5. Charge Densities in a Semiconductor - Explores the principle of electrical neutrality and how charge densities are balanced within semiconductors using practical examples.
6. Conductivity of a Semiconductor - Breaks down the concept of semiconductor conductivity, introduces mobility, and presents a solved example to reinforce understanding.
7. Conductivity of Semiconductors Numerical (Part 1) - Walks through a fully worked numerical problem on calculating semiconductor conductivity, ideal for exam practice.
8. Conductivity of Semiconductors Numerical (Part 2) - Continues with another detailed numerical example, solidifying your problem-solving approach to conductivity questions.

title: Semiconductor Diode | Chapter 2 | Analog Electronics
description:
This comprehensive playlist is dedicated to Chapter 2 of Analog Electronics, Semiconductor Diode. It covers the fundamental and advanced aspects of PN junction diodes, a cornerstone topic in electronics and semiconductor physics. This chapter is crucial for understanding the working principles of modern electronic devices and is frequently tested in GATE, UGC NET, PSUs, and university-level exams.
The series is ideal for Engineering and Science students (especially in Electronics, Computer Science, Electrical, or Instrumentation), as well as competitive exam aspirants and early-career professionals looking to reinforce core electronics concepts.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. PN Junction Diode (No Applied Bias) - Explains the physical formation of the PN junction, introduces key concepts like diffusion, drift, depletion region, and barrier potential in the absence of external voltage.
2. Barrier Potential - Dives deeper into the concept of built-in potential, derives expressions, and includes numerical problems with thermal voltage calculations.
3. Width of Depletion Region - Derives the mathematical expression for depletion width and illustrates it with a solved numerical problem.
4. PN Junction Diode (Forward-Bias Condition) - Analyzes how forward bias affects the depletion region, barrier potential, diode current, and reverse saturation current.
5. PN Junction Diode (Reverse-Bias Condition) - Covers the reverse bias state of a diode and compares behavior across no-bias, forward-bias, and reverse-bias conditions.
6. Semiconductor Diode - Introduces the diode symbol, current-voltage relationship, and provides an example problem for better understanding.
7. V-I Characteristics of PN Junction Diode - Presents forward and reverse bias V-I curves, discusses breakdown mechanisms like Zener breakdown and PIV.
8. Effects of Temperature on V-I Characteristics - Explores how temperature influences diode characteristics in both bias conditions and compares materials like Si, Ge, and GaAs.
9. Ideal Vs Practical Diode - Distinguishes between ideal and real-world diodes, explains resistance in various bias conditions, and presents approximation models.
10. Diode Equivalent Circuits - Introduces different models of diode equivalent circuits and explains when and how to use them in circuit analysis.
11. Load Line Analysis of Diode - Explains the concept of the load line, how to plot it, and understand its role in determining the diode‚Äôs operating point.
12. Load Line Analysis (Numerical Problem) - Solves a numerical example involving the calculation of operating point and voltage across load resistance.
13. DC or Static Resistance of a Diode - Explains how DC resistance changes with the operating point and includes methods and formulas for calculation.
14. AC or Dynamic Resistance of a Diode - Discusses how the diode responds to alternating signals and how to compute dynamic resistance.
15. Average AC Resistance of a Diode - Covers the concept of average AC resistance, the conditions under which it is used, and its calculation technique.

title: Diode Applications | Chapter 3 | Analog Electronics
description:
This comprehensive playlist on Diode Applications, is designed to build a strong conceptual and practical foundation in semiconductor diode applications, essential for students in Electronics, Electrical, and Computer Science Engineering, as well as aspirants of competitive exams like GATE, ESE, and UGC NET. It serves as a critical bridge between theory and application, covering rectifier circuits, voltage regulation, waveform shaping, and signal conditioning using diodes.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Series Diode Configurations - Learn how to analyze series diode circuits using the constant voltage drop model with examples.
2. Series Diode Configuration (Examples) - Practice numerical problems and understand voltage at different circuit points.
3. Parallel Diode Configurations - Analyze basic parallel diode configuration with a practical example.
4. Parallel and Series-Parallel Configuration of Diodes (Examples) - Solve mixed configuration problems involving series and parallel diodes.
5. Introduction to Diode Rectifier Circuits - Understand rectification, DC power supply stages, and types of rectifiers.
6. Half Wave Rectifier - Study working of half-wave rectifier and output waveform for ideal and practical diode models.
7. Half Wave Rectifier (RMS Load Current & RMS Load Voltage) - Learn how to compute RMS values of current and voltage.
8. Half Wave Rectifier (Form Factor) - Discover form factor meaning and calculations for rectified outputs.
9. Half Wave Rectifier (Ripple Factor) - Understand and derive ripple factor for half-wave rectifiers.
10. Half Wave Rectifier (Efficiency & PIV) - Derive efficiency and peak inverse voltage expressions.
11. Full Wave Bridge Rectifier - Analyze bridge rectifier with multiple diode models.
12. Full Wave Center-Tapped Rectifier - Explore working and waveform analysis of center-tapped rectifiers.
13. Full Wave Rectifier (DC Load Current & DC Load Voltage) - Calculate average (DC) load current and voltage.
14. Full Wave Rectifier (RMS Load Current & RMS Load Voltage) - Compute RMS values in full-wave rectification.
15. Full Wave Rectifier (Form Factor & Ripple Factor) - Understand waveform smoothness via form and ripple factor.
16. Full Wave Rectifier (Efficiency & PIV) - Derive efficiency and PIV for both bridge and center-tapped configurations.
17. Diode Rectifier Circuits (Numerical Problem) - Solve comprehensive numerical problems related to rectifier performance.
18. Introduction to Zener Diodes - Learn Zener diode characteristics, symbol, breakdown mechanisms, and comparisons.
19. Effects of Temperature on Zener Voltage - Understand temperature coefficients and their impact on zener voltage.
20. Zener Diode as Voltage Regulator (Part 1) - Analyze fixed-input fixed-load circuits using Zener diode regulation.
21. Zener Diode as Voltage Regulator (Part 2) - Evaluate performance under fixed input and variable load conditions.
22. Zener Diode as Voltage Regulator (Part 3) - Study input voltage variation with fixed load resistance.
23. Zener Diode as Voltage Regulator (Part 4) - Handle scenarios with both input voltage and load resistance varying.
24. Zener Diode Numerical Problems (Part 1) - Solve circuit-level numerical problems involving Zener diodes.
25. Zener Diode Numerical Problems (Part 2) - Continue with more applied Zener circuit problem-solving.
26. Voltage Multiplier Circuits (Half Wave Voltage Doubler) - Learn working of half-wave voltage doubler circuits.
27. Voltage Multiplier Circuits (Full Wave Voltage Doubler) - Understand full-wave doubling and compare with half-wave counterparts.
28. Voltage Multiplier Circuits (Voltage Tripler & Quadrupler) - Analyze advanced voltage multiplier circuits for higher output.
29. Introduction to Clippers - Get introduced to clipper circuits, their types, and uses.
30. Unbiased Series Clippers - Analyze unbiased series clipper with ideal and practical diode behavior.
31. Biased Series Clippers - Extend to biased versions for waveform shaping.
32. Unbiased Parallel Clippers - Understand parallel clipper operation and waveform outputs.
33. Biased Parallel Clippers - Explore biased parallel clipper analysis and output plots.
34. Zener Diode Clipping Circuits - Apply Zener diodes in clipping circuits and analyze outputs.
35. Combination Clipper Circuits - Study advanced clipper circuits combining multiple types.
36. Transfer Characteristics of Clipper Circuit - Learn to derive and plot transfer characteristics of clipping circuits.
37. Introduction to Clampers - Understand the function and design of clamper circuits.
38. Positive & Negative Clamper Circuits - Analyze both types of clampers with waveform shifts.
39. Biased Clamper Circuit - Add biasing to clampers for controlled waveform positioning.
40. Clampers (Solved Problem) - Conclude with numerical examples based on clamper circuits.

title: Bipolar Junction Transistor | Chapter 4 | Analog Electronics
description:
This curated playlist offers a comprehensive introduction to Bipolar Junction Transistors (BJTs) an essential component of Analog Electronics and a foundational topic for students pursuing Electronics, Electrical, or Computer Science Engineering. Whether you're preparing for competitive exams like GATE, UGC NET, ESE, or building a strong conceptual base as an early-career electronics professional, this series is tailored to deliver clarity and practical understanding.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Introduction to Bipolar Junction Transistors (BJT) - Covers the invention, structure, symbols, and operation regions of BJT including key differences between npn and pnp transistors.
2. Working of Transistors - Explains the fundamental working of npn transistors in the active region, detailing emitter, base, and collector currents.
3. Common-Base Configuration of a Transistor - Introduces the CB configuration, voltage symbols, and defines current gain (Œ±) in active mode.
4. CB Transistor (Input Characteristics & Early Effect) - Discusses input characteristics of CB transistors and explains the Early effect and base width modulation.
5. CB Transistor (Output Characteristics) - Focuses on output characteristics of common-base configuration with detailed I-V curve analysis.
6. Transistor Amplifying Action - Covers input/output resistance, current/voltage amplification principles, and transistor as an amplifier.
7. Common-Emitter Configuration of a Transistor - Introduces CE configuration, explains current amplification factor (Œ≤), and compares leakage currents with CB.
8. Common-Emitter Transistor (Input Characteristics) - Discusses CE input characteristics and the manifestation of Early effect in this configuration.
9. Common-Emitter Transistor (Output Characteristics) - Explains CE output characteristics and describes the active, cutoff, and saturation regions in detail.
10. Common-Collector Configuration of a Transistor - Describes CC configuration, its applications, and explains why its output is similar to CE configuration. Defines amplification factor (Œ≥).

title: DC Biasing of Transistors | Chapter 5 | Analog Electronics
description:
This in-depth playlist covers DC Biasing of Transistors, a crucial topic in Analog Electronics that lays the foundation for designing stable and efficient transistor-based amplifiers. Mastering transistor biasing is essential for students of Electronics, Electrical, and Computer Science Engineering, especially those preparing for GATE, UGC NET, ESE, and PSU exams, as well as for early-career engineers and circuit design enthusiasts.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Relation between Œ±, Œ≤ and Œ≥ - Explains the interrelation between transistor current gains across CB, CE, and CC configurations for both AC and DC operations.
2. DC Biasing, Load Line & Operating Point of Transistors - Introduces the concept of biasing, its necessity, and methods to determine the Q-point using input and output load lines.
3. Fixed-Bias Configuration of a Transistor - Details current and voltage calculations in a fixed-bias circuit and analyzes its behavior with a step-by-step breakdown.
4. Fixed-Bias Configuration (Solved Problem) - A numerical example that reinforces the fixed-bias concepts and helps in problem-solving for exam preparation.
5. Emitter-Bias Configuration - Compares emitter bias with fixed bias, and shows how to calculate the operating point with the help of emitter resistance.
6. Emitter-Bias Configuration (Solved Problem) - Solves a practical problem on emitter-bias configuration, demonstrating application of theoretical concepts.
7. Collector Feedback Biasing - Explores this self-regulating biasing scheme and outlines its benefits and drawbacks with numerical analysis.

title: Zener Diode

title: Voltage Multiplier Circuits

title: Clampers

description:
Understanding Cascaded Systems is essential for analyzing and designing multi-stage amplifier circuits, an important topic in Analog Electronics and circuit theory. This playlist introduces learners to the concept of cascading amplifiers, providing a systematic approach to evaluating the performance of such systems through key parameters like total voltage gain, total current gain, and individual stage behavior.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Cascaded Systems - Introduces the concept of cascading in amplifier circuits and explains how to compute total voltage and current gain across multiple stages.
2. Cascaded Systems (Solved Problem) - A comprehensive numerical example demonstrating the calculation of individual loaded voltage gains, total voltage gain, and total current gain for a cascaded amplifier system.

title: Junction Field-Effect Transistors (JFET)
description:
This playlist offers a comprehensive and conceptual understanding of Junction Field-Effect Transistors (JFETs), a cornerstone topic in Analog Electronics. Designed to help learners transition smoothly from Bipolar Junction Transistors (BJTs) to Field-Effect Transistors, this series dives deep into the structure, working principles, and electrical characteristics of JFETs.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Introduction to Field-Effect Transistors (FETs) - Introduces the fundamentals of FETs, their classification, operating principles, and how they differ from BJTs in terms of control mechanism and electrical behavior.
2. Construction and Working of JFET - Explains the physical structure of an n-channel JFET, including terminal definitions and depletion layer formation using relatable analogies.
3. Working of JFET (Zero Voltage at the Gate) - Demonstrates how a JFET operates when the gate-to-source voltage is zero, emphasizing changes in depletion width and current flow.
4. Pinch-off Voltage - Covers the concept of pinch-off condition, how drain current saturates, and explains the graphical drain current vs. drain-source voltage curve.
5. JFET as a Current Source - Illustrates how a JFET behaves like a current source under certain operating conditions and includes the solution to a prior homework problem.
6. Working of JFET (Negative Voltage at the Gate) - Shows how applying a negative gate-source voltage affects the depletion layer and modulates current through the JFET.
7. Output or Drain Characteristics of JFET - Breaks down the four key operating regions of JFETs‚ÄîOhmic, Active (Saturation), Cut-off, and Breakdown, and plots their effects on device behavior.
8. JFET as Voltage-Controlled Resistor - Analyzes the JFET's Ohmic region where it acts as a voltage-controlled resistor, and discusses how input voltage modulates its resistance.
9. Transfer Characteristics of JFET - Explains how drain current varies with gate-source voltage using Shockley‚Äôs equation, and compares it with the transfer behavior of BJTs.
10. BJT Vs JFET - A side-by-side comparative analysis of BJTs and JFETs based on symbols, impedance, gain, power consumption, sensitivity, and more.
11. JFET Solved Problems (Part 1) - Walkthrough of numerical problems focused on calculating drain current and gate-to-source resistance for different control voltages.
12. JFET Solved Problems (Part 2) - Covers the concept of transconductance and includes a GATE-level numerical for calculating JFET output voltage and gm.

title: Metal-Oxide Semiconductor Field-Effect Transistors (MOSFET)
description:
This comprehensive playlist on MOSFETs (Metal-Oxide Semiconductor Field-Effect Transistors) is designed to help students and professionals master one of the most vital components in Analog Electronics and VLSI design. Whether you're preparing for GATE, UGC NET, ESE, or strengthening your foundational knowledge for a career in electronics or computer science, this series walks you through every essential concept of enhancement-type and depletion-type MOSFETs, from theory to problem-solving.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Introduction to Field-Effect Transistors (FETs) - An overview of FETs, their classification, properties, comparison with BJTs, and their role as voltage-controlled unipolar devices.
2. Construction & Working of Enhancement-Type MOSFET (Part 1) - Explains the structure and operation of n-channel enhancement-type MOSFETs, including substrate, terminals, and channel formation.
3. Construction & Working of Enhancement-Type MOSFET (Part 2) - Continues the explanation of enhancement-mode MOSFETs, focusing on threshold voltage, complete circuit structure, and the pinch-off mechanism.
4. Drain Characteristics of Enhancement-Type MOSFET - Discusses the output characteristics of enhancement-mode MOSFETs across triode, saturation, and cut-off regions.
5. Transfer Characteristics & Symbols of Enhancement Type MOSFETs - Explores the transfer curve and reviews key symbols associated with n-channel enhancement-type MOSFETs.
6. Construction of Depletion-Type MOSFET - Introduces the physical structure of n-channel depletion-mode MOSFETs and compares them with enhancement-mode devices.
7. Working of Depletion-Type MOSFET - Explains the behavior of depletion-type MOSFETs under zero, negative, and positive gate-source voltages with comparisons to JFETs.
8. Drain & Transfer Characteristics of Depletion-Type MOSFET - Illustrates output and transfer characteristics of depletion-mode MOSFETs, including maximum drain current analysis and symbolic representations.
9. MOSFET Solved Problems (Part 1) - Solves numerical problems related to both enhancement and depletion-type MOSFETs, focusing on current behavior and comparative analysis.
10. MOSFET Solved Problems (Part 2) - Dives into more advanced problems covering threshold voltage, saturated drain current, and current equations in different operating regions.

title: Propositional Logic | Chapter 1 | Discrete Mathematics

20. Propositional Logic (Solved Problem 4) - Analyzes and solves a GATE 2004 logic problem.
21. Propositional Logic (Solved Problem 5) - GATE 2005 problem solving using logical techniques.
22. Propositional Logic (Solved Problem 6) - Provides a stepwise solution to a GATE 2009 logic question.
23. Propositional Logic (Solved Problem 7) - Solves a GATE 2016 problem using propositional concepts.
24. Rules of Inference - Basic Terminology - Defines arguments, premises, conclusions, and distinguishes valid vs. invalid arguments.

title: First Order Logic | Chapter 2 | Discrete Mathematics

26. Nested Quantifiers (Translating English Statements)-Example 2-Example-based walkthrough of the translation process.
27. Nested Quantifiers (Translating English Statements)-Example 3-Applies logical form to English statements with multiple quantifiers.
28. Nested Quantifiers (Translating English Statements)-Example 4-Solves a GATE 2005 question on nested quantifier translation.
29. Nested Quantifiers (Translating English Statements)-Example 5-Final example covering complex translation using multiple quantifiers.

title: Set Theory | Chapter 3 | Discrete Mathematics

title: Relations | Chapter 4 | Discrete Mathematics
description:

title: Partial Ordering | Chapter 5 | Discrete Mathematics
description:
This playlist focuses on Partial Ordering, a key topic in Discrete Mathematics, fundamental to understanding hierarchical structures, data organization, and logical reasoning in Computer Science. Partial ordering is a cornerstone in areas like database theory, lattice theory, graph theory, and is frequently tested in GATE, UGC NET, and other technical competitive exams.
Whether you're aiming to master discrete math for academic excellence or seeking to crack competitive exams like GATE CSE, UGC NET CS, or other logical reasoning tests, this playlist offers an organized and insightful approach.

title: Lattices | Chapter 6 | Discrete Mathematics

title: First Order Logic - Solved Problems

title: Nested Quantifiers

title: The Resolution Principle

Equivalent resistance is a core concept that helps simplify complex resistor networks into manageable forms, making circuit analysis easier and more systematic. A strong command over this topic is highly valuable for engineering students, competitive exam aspirants (GATE, ESE, UGC NET, PSU exams), and early-career professionals in Electrical, Electronics, and Computer Science fields.

title: Solved Problems on Equivalent Capacitance
description:
This playlist provides a comprehensive set of solved problems on Equivalent Capacitance, an essential concept in Network Theory and Circuit Analysis. Equivalent capacitance helps simplify complex capacitor networks into single, manageable values, making analysis easier for both academic and practical applications. A strong understanding of this topic is crucial for engineering students, competitive exam aspirants (GATE, ESE, UGC NET, PSU exams), and early-career professionals in Electrical, Electronics, and Computer Science fields.

This playlist presents a comprehensive collection of solved problems on Sinusoidal Steady-State analysis, a crucial topic in Network Theory. title: Superposition Theorem

The Reciprocity Theorem is one of the fundamental theorems in Network Theory, widely applied in circuit analysis to simplify problem-solving. It establishes the principle that the response (current or voltage) in one branch of a linear, bilateral network due to a source in another branch is the same as the response in the second branch if the same source is applied in the first. Designed for students, Computer Science aspirants, GATE and UGC NET candidates, ESE learners, and early-career professionals, these lectures break down concepts step by step, ensuring clarity for both beginners and those revising for exams.
Whether you‚Äôre preparing for GATE, ESE, UGC NET, campus placements, or other aptitude-driven tests, mastering ratio and proportion builds a strong foundation for higher-level problem-solving. By the end of this playlist, you‚Äôll be equipped not just with the formulas, but also the intuition to apply them efficiently.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Introduction to Aptitude and Reasoning - Explains what aptitude and reasoning are, their significance, and the major categories included in competitive exam syllabi.
2. Ratio - Covers the basics of ratios, their applications, how to calculate compound ratios (A:B:C), and shortcut techniques.
3. Ratio (Solved Problems) ‚Äì Part 1 - Walks through detailed solutions of ratio-based problems, including multi-variable ratios like A:B:C:D and mixture problems.
4. Ratio (Solved Problems) ‚Äì Part 2 - More practice with advanced ratio questions, including coin distribution and age-related ratio problems.
5. Proportion - Introduces the concept of proportion, different types (third, fourth, mean), and essential rules like Componendo and Dividendo.
6. Direct and Indirect Proportion - Explains direct vs. inverse proportion with simple definitions and practical examples.
7. Proportion (Solved Problems) - Step-by-step problem-solving on proportion-based questions, including exam-style numerical problems.
8. Ratio and Proportion (10 Solved Problems) - A mixed set of solved questions that combine ratio and proportion, ideal for exam practice and revision.

title: Number Systems | Chapter 2 | Aptitude & Reasoning
description:
This playlist provides a complete guide to Number Systems, one of the most fundamental and high-weightage topics in Aptitude and Reasoning. A strong command over number systems is essential for competitive exams (GATE, ESE, UGC NET, SSC, Banking, and campus placements) as well as for building problem-solving skills crucial in computer science and technical interviews.
This chapter is crafted for students, competitive exam aspirants, and early-career professionals who want to gain mastery over number systems. By the end of the playlist, you‚Äôll not only understand the theory but also know how to apply shortcut methods and systematic approaches to solve exam-level problems quickly and accurately.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Classification of Numbers - Introduces different types of numbers‚Äîreal, complex, rational, irrational, integers, fractions, surds, and more.
2. Prime and Composite Numbers - Explains the difference between prime and composite numbers, why 1 is neither, and lists primes under 100.
3. Number of Factors (Part 1) - Shortcut methods to calculate the total number of factors of a given composite number.
4. Number of Factors (Part 2) - Focuses on calculating prime factors of numbers with solved examples and practice questions.
5. Number of Even and Odd Factors - Shows how to determine the total even and odd factors for numbers like 48 and 60.
6 Power of Prime Number in a Factorial - Formula-based approach to find the highest power of a prime number in factorials (e.g., highest power of 2 in 4!, 3 in 80!).
7. Power of Composite Number in a Factorial - Step-by-step method for calculating the power of composite numbers in factorials with solved examples.
8. The Base System - Explains digits, number representation, base/radix systems, and why number systems are important.
9. The Base System - Addition - Demonstrates addition of numbers in different bases, highlighting rules and examples.
10. The Base System - Subtraction - Covers subtraction in decimal, binary, and septal systems, with concepts of borrow, minuend, and subtrahend.
11. The Base System (Solved Problems) - Solved problems involving finding the base of number systems and performing arithmetic operations.
12. Number of Trailing Zeros in a Factorial - Explains how to determine the total zeros at the end of factorial numbers.
13. Cyclicity of Numbers (Part 1) - Introduces cyclicity and applies it to find unit digits of powers involving numbers 0-3.
14. Cyclicity of Numbers (Part 2) - Continues cyclicity with numbers 4-9 and demonstrates shortcut applications.
15. Unit Place Calculation (Part 1) - Uses cyclicity rules to find the unit digit of large powers systematically.
16. Unit Place Calculation (Part 2) - Applies cyclicity of 4 and 9 in unit digit problems, with practical examples.
17. Unit Place Calculation (Part 3) - Covers cyclicities of 2, 3, 7, and 8 for efficient unit digit calculations.
18. Unit Place Calculation (Solved Problems) - Brings together theory and practice through solved exam-style problems on unit digit determination.

Videos Included in This Playlist:

1. The Base System - Addition - Explains addition in different bases, including decimal, binary, and octal, with rules for carry and the divide-by-base method.
1. The Base System - Subtraction - Covers subtraction in decimal, binary, and septal systems, explaining how borrow works along with minuend, subtrahend, and difference.

title: Cyclicity of Numbers
description:

Mastering cyclicity not only saves time but also builds strong problem-solving skills for quantitative aptitude and reasoning.

Videos Included in This Playlist:

2. Cyclicity of Numbers (Part 2) - Continues with cyclicity patterns for digits 4 through 9, complete with examples to show how the patterns repeat and how to apply them effectively in exams.

title: Unit Place Calculation
description:

Such problems are common in competitive exams like GATE, UGC NET, SSC, Banking, CAT, and campus placements, where quick mental calculation is essential.
Building on the concept of Cyclicity of Numbers, the lectures explain how unit digits follow predictable repeating patterns. You‚Äôll learn how to handle unit digit problems involving powers of 2, 3, 4, 7, 8, and 9, with step-by-step demonstrations and solved examples. By the end, you‚Äôll be able to solve unit digit questions with speed and confidence, avoiding unnecessary long multiplications.

Videos Included in This Playlist:
1. Unit Place Calculation (Part 1) - Introduces unit digit calculations using cyclicity and demonstrates how large powers can be simplified.
2. Unit Place Calculation (Part 2) - Explains unit digit shortcuts for powers of 4 and 9, supported with examples.
3. Unit Place Calculation (Part 3) - Covers unit digit calculations for powers of 2, 3, 7, and 8, showing how their cyclic patterns repeat.
4. Unit Place Calculation (Solved Problems) - Focuses entirely on practice, with multiple solved problems to reinforce learning and boost exam readiness.
