title: Practical x64 Assembly and C++ Tutorials
description:
A bunch of tutorials on how to use x64 Assembly (Assembler) to increase the speed of your programs. I want to make practical tutorials, not 'Hello World!'. Teaching people to 'Hello World!' in Assembly won't speed up their algorithms. I hope to get to MMX, SSE2/3/4, AVX and any other SIMD extensions. I want to show that hand coding Assembly is not difficult, it makes more sense in many aspects than C++. The rules and restrictions placed on programmer's in high level languages all go out the window, in Assembly, we do what we like!

Please, please, please turn on annotations as when I make my many mistakes, I point them out with annotations.

title: C++ Tutorials
description:
A collection of C++ programming tutorials aimed at Windows application development using Visual Studio for beginners.

I wish to teach people how to create Windows applications. Programming a real desktop application is very different from using the examples generally presented in programming tutorials. If you have been through a few C++ tutorial series and  are still left with the "where do I begin?" question when you sit down to create an application, these tutorials are for you.

Whether you are a beginner or an experienced programmer, I hope you will find new and interesting information herein.

I hope also to inspire people and show that programming is not mundane. These computer languages are amongst mankind's greatest and most powerful inventions. I hope to instill this enthusiasm in others.

Golden Crocoduck nominees
description:
Annual award for the Biggest Breach of the Ninth Commandment in Pursuit of the Creationist Cause. Nominations will be highlighted throughout the year, and the winner announced on October 28, the Feast Day of St Jude Thaddeus. To nominate a breach, please send me a personal message with three things: 1) The URL of the video  2) The exact nature of the breach  3) The time on the video where the breach can be found. 
   Beliefs, stupidity, opinion and being a dickhead are not grounds for a nomination, although these qualities may enhance a nominee's chances of making it to the final shortlist. A breach of the 9th Commandment is simply a falsehood, and for a Golden Crocoduck it has to underpin an argument that promotes creationism.

title: Our Origins Made Easy
description: This series explains the science of where we came from -- from the Big Bang to the human migration out of Africa. How stars and planets were formed, how life could have originated, how and why it evolved, and how it led to us -- along with the evidence that supports these conclusions. I originally made this series because I was on a discussion forum with creationists who clearly had no understanding of the science, and I felt it needed to be explained, and set against religious beliefs that attempt to undermine it. The series can be found in DVD quality at http://www.youtube.com/user/madeeasyseries. Feel free to download and copy under creative commons rules.

title: Climate change explained, and the myths debunked
description: There is a lot of inaccurate nonsense about climate science written in blogs and the media, whether exaggerating the effects of climate change or seeking to undermine the science behind it. This series checks the sources of these claims and shows how they have been misinterpreted or deliberately altered.  I have no expertise in climatology, I am a former science journalist, so checking facts is what I do. And I always cite these sources so you can check them for yourselves. Along the way, I explain the real science as relayed by researchers in published papers, in a way that makes it easy to understand.

The Occult Philosophy of Agrippa
description:
Syllabus - https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Sl89CbNsmF9TCLIyImiOOGj1PjFjPnIeEtMFy2_mIS4/edit?usp=sharing
Sources - https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1Jmnbw3ft7a8mUQnELLARcELy3Na_ORCk?usp=sharing

Between Skepticism and Mysticism:  An Introduction to the Occult Philosophy of Cornelius Agrippa

The Three Books of Occult Philosophy (De Occulta Philosophia - DOP) is rightly lauded by both academics and practitioners as the cornerstone of all modern occultism.  Despite this, the DOP goes tremendously understudied, making it much more celebrated than understood.  By extension, the totality of Agrippa‚Äôs occult philosophy - represented by his other theological, philosophical and hermetic writings - suffers all the more from lack of modern editions and translations. Finally, understanding Agrippa‚Äôs thought overall is greatly complicated by his infamous turn toward radical skepticism and fideism, seemingly his mature philosophical and theological position.  This series of lectures aims to provide a systematic and comprehensive introduction to the occult philosophy of Cornelius Agrippa.

title: Introduction to Ethics
description:
These videos are the lecture portion of an introductory-level philosophy course: Introduction to Ethics. The videos can be watched an any order, but they were designed to be watched in the specific order in which they appear here. 

Here are the readings for this course, which are divided into three units:

Unit #1:
The Content of Morality: What is the morally right thing to do?

Jeremy Bentham, Introduction to the Principles of Morals and Legislation, Ch. 1*

Jeremy Bentham, The Rationale of Reward, Book III, Ch. 1, just paragraph 8*

Robert Nozick, The Experience Machine *

Jeremy Bentham, Offenses Against One's Self, selection*

J.J.C. Smart,  Utilitarianism and Justice*

Peter Singer, Famine, Affluence, and Morality

Onora O‚ÄôNeill, Kant on Treating People as Ends In Themselves, selection*

Unit #2:
The Authority of Morality: Why should we do the morally right thing?

Aristotle, Nicomachean Ethics, Book I, selections*

Unit #3:
The Objectivity of Morality: Is morality relative in some way?

David Hume,  A Treatise of Human Nature, Book III, Part 1, ¬ß1, selections.

title: HLA Hart's 1961 book - The Concept of Law
description:
I have only recorded lecture about some of the chapters, starting with chapter 2. So if you don't see chapter 1, that's because that chapter is boring, and you don't need to have read it to understand the important stuff that happens in the rest of the book. 

The overall rundown is this:
Chapter 2 - Summary of John Austin's theory of law
Chapter 3 - Attack on Austin's theory
Chapter 4 - More attack on Austin's theory
Chapter 5 - Hart's own theory of law
Chapter 6 - More of Hart's own theory of law

These are the only chapters about which I made lecture videos, because these are the chapters that, in my opinion matter the most. And also these are probably the chapters that will be most emphasized in a typical jurisprudence course.

title: Philosophy of Language
description: Language is perhaps the single greatest ability that our species has. But words are just bits of ink on a page, or soundwaves emanating from our mouths, or the movement of our body parts in sign language. How can these things be *about* the world? How do names refer to people and objects? What about words or phrases‚Äîlike ‚ÄúYay!‚Äù and ‚ÄúBoo!‚Äù‚Äîthat are meaningful, but do not seem to refer at all? And how is it possible that mere speech can change the way the world is, such as when an officiant pronounces two people married, or when congress declares war? In this course we will read and discuss answers to these questions developed by famous philosophers, and we will develop answers of our own.
